# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-royal-australia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria provides emergency medical response to more than 5.9 million people in an area of more than 227,000 square kilometres.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The service is funded by fees for the cost of transport and treatment by paramedics, with paid memberships entitling holders to free services.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Private health insurance or compensation providers such as the Transport Accident Commission or WorkCover may cover out-of-pocket costs, however Australia's universal health insurance scheme (Medicare) does not fund ambulance services.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] A formal ambulance service began in Victoria in 1883.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Over the years services were provided by St John Ambulance, Civil Ambulance Service and a multitude local area ambulance services.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In the 1980s the Metropolitan Ambulance Service was formed from a number of smaller area services; and 16 regional services were amalgamated into five.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In 1997, the rural services were consolidated to one rural service, Rural Ambulance Victoria.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 22 April 2008, Premier John Brumby and Health Minister Daniel Andrews announced a record funding boost of over $185m, including two new helicopter services, 26 new ambulance stations and over 300 new paramedics.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In addition, it was announced that the way the state's ambulance services work was to be changed with Metropolitan Ambulance Service and Rural Ambulance Victoria becoming one organisation, Ambulance Victoria.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 26 May this decision was confirmed, with the consolidated service commencing operation on 1 July 2008.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria's primary function is to respond to emergency incidents and its secondary function is medical transport (non-emergency) requests.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria has more than 260 ambulance branches located across Victoria.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In 2015–2016, Ambulance Victoria's workforce was 3,438 paramedics and 578 MICA paramedics.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In addition, Ambulance Victoria employed 723 casual ACO and there were 357 CERT volunteers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria assesses each emergency incident on receipt of the 000 call, designating the incident a code depending on the urgency/severity, and publishes its response times for each quarter of the year on the internet.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria operates a Bicycle Response Unit in pre-planned operations for public events in Melbourne with large crowds.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The unit was established in the lead up to the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In 2012, a Paramedic Motorcycle Unit was trialled in inner city Melbourne operating two Piaggio MP3 three wheeled motorbikes.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The trial was successful with the BMW F700GS motorcycle selected to be the unit's motorcycle to operate in the inner Melbourne area mainly in the councils of City of Melbourne and City of Port Phillip.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria's emergency and non-emergency patient transport communications are handled by Triple Zero Victoria communication centres in Ballarat, East Burwood and Williams Landing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance communications functions include 000 Emergency call-taking, non-emergency patient transport requests, and ambulance dispatch for emergency and non-emergency vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Modern emergency services communications is highly advanced, and communications staff use a wide range of technologies including digital and analogue radio, telephones, pagers, and advanced computer and GPS systems.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Many emergency services vehicles, including ambulances, are fitted with mobile data terminals that enable them to view information, read messages sent by call-takers and dispatchers, and be notified of updates immediately as they become available.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] A number of communication services used by Ambulance Victoria, such as digital radio and mobile data terminals, are not available outside metropolitan Melbourne.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Their most common vehicle is the Mercedes-Benz Sprinter.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] This vehicle is the frontline vehicle for all of Victoria as they carry one patient at a time with loads of medical equipment, which is usually staffed by two paramedics.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] There are also different models including models with bull bars/push bumpers for better use in rural areas.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] AV also operates Mobile Intensive Care Ambulances which are staffed by more specially trained paramedics and different equipment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] They also operate Non-Emergency Patient Transport Ambulances (NEPT) and Clinical Transport Services units (CTS).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] For more complex patients, AV has Complex Patient Ambulance Vehicles (CPAV) and Adult Retrieval Services (AR) both are similar to the standard general ambulances.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The CPAV units include a lift platform at the back instead of regular doors, the AR unit has more specialist equipment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Introduced in 2017, AV teamed up with The Royal Melbourne Hospital, the Stroke Foundation and numerous other agencies to create a $7 Million Mobile Stroke Unit Ambulance (MSU).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The state-of-the-art vehicle include specialist equipment tailored to stroke patients.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In the ambulance is a built-in CT-Scanner.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Two paramedics staff the ambulance (including a MICA paramedic), a CT radiographer, a stroke neurologist and a stroke nurse specialist.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The first MSU is currently running as car 6600.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria has a fleet of helicopters and fixed wing aircraft operated by Air Ambulance Victoria (AAV) based out of Essendon Airport in Melbourne with helicopters strategically placed in regional Victoria.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In addition, the helicopters respond to search and rescue incidents, able to utilise the winch, including sea rescues.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] AAV operates five twin engine AgustaWestland AW139 helicopters provided by Babcock Mission Critical Services Australasia.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The helicopters were introduced from 2016 to replace the four Bell 412EP helicopters and also one Eurocopter AS365N3 Dauphin helicopter that had been operated in partnership with the Victoria Police Air Wing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Helicopter operations commenced in 1970 with a Bell 206A JetRanger known as the 'Angel of Mercy' based on the Mornington Peninsula operated from Tyabb Airport.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In 1980, a Hughes 500D was operated in the La Trobe Valley, later a Bell 206 Long Ranger and from 1985 a Bell 412 known as Helimed 1 later renamed to HEMS 2.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In 1986, AAV entered a partnership with the Victoria Police Air Wing to use a Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin which would respond to both police and ambulance incidents with ambulance given priority known as HEMS 1 and replacing the 'Angel of Mercy'.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Two helicopters were configured for the aeromedical role with one as a spare.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In 2001, a Bell 412EP was operated from Bendigo airport known as HEMS 3.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In 2009, a Bell 412EP was operated from Warrnambool Airport known as HEMS 4 and a second Bell 412EP was operated from Essendon known as HEMS 5 to transport critically ill patients from rural hospitals to Melbourne.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] In January 2017, the final of the five new AgustaWestland AW139s entered service replacing the Victoria Police Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin and ending the partnership.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The aircraft are staffed by MICA Flight Paramedics who are trained to administer blood, conduct ultrasounds, complete complex procedures and perform winch rescues.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] AAV has operated four Beechcraft Super King Air B200s, provided by Pel-Air Aviation, from its Essendon headquarters since 2011 and can reach most of Victoria within an hour.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] They are used mainly for transporting patients from rural towns to the major hospitals in Melbourne and can carry two stretcher patients and two walking patients.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] This service includes bringing people to Melbourne for regular treatments such as oncology and dialysis while also facilitating acute medical conditions requiring surgery or the transfer of injured patients from rural hospitals to specialist care.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The service now reaches to more than 86 towns within Victoria while also servicing southern New South Wales, northern Tasmania and some parts of South Australia.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] The aircraft are typically staffed by advanced life support (ALS) paramedics.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 23 March 2016, the Victorian Auditor-General tabled a damning report into "Bullying and Harassment in the Health Sector".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Ambulance Victoria was one of four Government Health Bodies that was audited as part of this report.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] As part of the audit, the Auditor General looked at the background of the issue, workplace culture, preventing bullying and harassment, responding to bullying and harassment and sector-wide collaboration and support.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 15 March 2016, chairman of the Board of Directors, Mr Ken Lay, AO, APM, acknowledged of the Audit and committed the Organisation to accepting all the recommendations of the Audit through the Ambulance and Policy Consultative Committee.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 26 October 2020, Allegations of widespread bullying, harassment and gross misconduct were public reported by The Age after 13 Paramedics raised an open letter to Mr Ken Lay, chairman of the board of directors.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 27 October 2020, the Victorian Equal Opportunity and Human Rights Commission announced that it had been asked to conduct a review into allegations of unlawful, discriminatory behaviour at Ambulance Victoria by.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 30 November 2020, The Commission released the terms of reference for its review of Ambulance Victoria.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Throughout the process, the commission has provided public updates regarding the review.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Volume 1 was released on 30 November 2021 by The commission.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] On 30 November 2021, The Commission noted that Ambulance Victoria had accepted all recommendations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance-victoria] Volume 2 was released in March 2022 by the commission.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] An **ambulance** is a medically equipped vehicle used to transport patients to treatment facilities, such as hospitals.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Typically, out-of-hospital medical care is provided to the patient during the transport.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances are used to respond to medical emergencies by emergency medical services (EMS), and can rapidly transport paramedics and other first responders, carry equipment for administering emergency care, and transport patients to hospital or other definitive care.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Most ambulances use a design based on vans or pickup trucks, though others take the form of motorcycles, buses, hearses, aircraft and boats.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances are generally considered emergency vehicles authorized to be equipped with emergency lights and sirens.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Generally, vehicles count as an ambulance if they can transport patients.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] However, it varies by jurisdiction as to whether a non-emergency patient transport vehicle (also called an ambulette) is counted as an ambulance.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These vehicles are not usually (although there are exceptions) equipped with life-support equipment, and are usually crewed by staff with fewer qualifications than the crew of emergency ambulances.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Conversely, EMS agencies may also have nontransporting EMS vehicles that cannot transport patients.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The term *ambulance* comes from the Latin word *ambulare* as meaning 'to walk or move about' which is a reference to early medical care where patients were moved by lifting or wheeling.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The word originally meant a moving hospital, which follows an army in its movements.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances (*ambulancias* in Spanish) were first used for emergency transport in 1487 by the Spanish forces during the siege of Málaga by the Catholic Monarchs against the Emirate of Granada.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] During the American Civil War vehicles for conveying the wounded off the field of battle were called ambulance wagons.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Field hospitals were still called ambulances during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870 and in the Serbo-Turkish war of 1876 even though the wagons were first referred to as ambulances about 1854 during the Crimean War.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The history of the ambulance begins in ancient times, with the use of carts to transport incurable patients by force.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances were first used for emergency transport in 1487 by the Spanish, and civilian variants were put into operation during the 1830s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Advances in technology throughout the 19th and 20th centuries led to modern self-powered ambulances.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances can be grouped into types depending on whether or not they transport patients, and under what conditions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulance design must take into account local conditions and infrastructure.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Maintained roads are necessary for road-going ambulances to arrive on scene and then transport the patient to a hospital, though in rugged areas four-wheel drive or all-terrain vehicles can be used.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Fuel must be available and service facilities are necessary to maintain the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Methods of summoning (e.g. telephone) and dispatching ambulances usually rely on electronic equipment, which itself often relies on an intact power grid.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances often have two stages of manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The first is frequently the manufacture of light or medium truck chassis-cabs or full-size vans (or in some places, cars) such as Mercedes-Benz, Nissan, Toyota, or Ford.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The second manufacturer (known as second stage manufacturer) modifies the vehicle (which is sometimes purchased incomplete, having no body or interior behind the driver's seat) and turns it into an ambulance by adding bodywork, emergency vehicle equipment, and interior fittings.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] This is done by one of two methods – either coachbuilding, where the modifications are started from scratch and built on to the vehicle, or using a modular system, where a pre-built 'box' is put on to the empty chassis of the ambulance, and then finished off.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Modern ambulances are typically powered by internal combustion engines, which can be powered by any conventional fuel, including diesel, gasoline or liquefied petroleum gas, depending on the preference of the operator and the availability of different options.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] As electric vehicles become more common ambulances are moving to electricity and can even be solar-powered with solar photovoltaic modules integrated into the rooftops.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Colder regions often use gasoline-powered engines, as diesels can be difficult to start when they are cold.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Warmer regions may favor diesel engines, as they are more efficient and more durable.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Diesel power is sometimes chosen due to safety concerns, after a series of fires involving gasoline-powered ambulances during the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These fires were ultimately attributed in part to gasoline's higher volatility in comparison to diesel fuel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The type of engine may be determined by the manufacturer: in the past two decades, Ford would only sell vehicles for ambulance conversion if they are diesel-powered.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Beginning in 2010, Ford will sell its ambulance chassis with a gasoline engine in order to meet emissions requirements.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In the United Kingdom, the National Health Service has set a target for all ambulances to be fully electric as part of the Net Zero campaign by 2045.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Many regions have prescribed standards which ambulances should, or must, meet in order to be used for their role.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These standards may have different levels which reflect the type of patient which the ambulance is expected to transport (for instance specifying a different standard for routine patient transport than high dependency), or may base standards on the size of vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] For instance, in Europe, the European Committee for Standardization publishes the standard CEN 1789, which specifies minimum compliance levels across the build of ambulance, including crash resistance, equipment levels, and exterior marking.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In the United States, standards for ambulance design have existed since 1976, where the standard is published by the General Services Administration and known as KKK-A-1822.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] This standard has been revised several times, and is currently in version 'F' change notice #13, known as KKK-A-1822F.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The National Fire Protection Association has also published a design standard, NFPA 1917, which offers an alternative to KKK-A-1822F.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The Commission on Accreditation of Ambulance Services (CAAS) has published its Ground Vehicle Standard for Ambulances v2.0, effective July 2019.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] This standard is similar to the KKK-A-1822F and NFPA 1917–2019 specifications.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The decision on which of the current (3) standards to require is left up to each individual state legislature or EMS director.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Some states have no specific requirement, while others specify which standard is acceptable.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Others, yet, allow the end user to decide which standard to comply to.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In the United States and Canada, there are four types of ambulances: Type I, Type II, Type III, and Type IV.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Type I is based on a heavy truck chassis-cab with a custom rear compartment that is often referred to as a "box" or "module", primarily used for Advanced Life Support (ALS) or Mobile Intensive Care Unit (MICU), as well as rescue work.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Type II is based on a commercial heavy-duty van with few modifications except for a raised roof and a secondary air conditioning unit for the rear of the vehicle, primarily used for Basic Life Support (BLS) and transfer of patients, though they are occasionally also used for ALS and rescue.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Type III is a van chassis-cab with a custom-made rear compartment, used for ALS and rescue.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Type IV is for *ad hoc* patient transfer using smaller utility vehicles selected for maneuverability in special environments such as dense crowds at events; these are uncommon and are not subject to federal regulations in the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The move towards standardisation is now reaching countries without a history of prescriptive codes, such as India, which approved its first national standard for ambulance construction in 2013.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances, like other emergency vehicles, are required to operate in most weather conditions, including those during which civilian drivers often elect to stay off the road.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Also, the ambulance crew's responsibilities to their patient often preclude their use of safety devices such as seat belts.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Research has shown that ambulances are more likely to be involved in motor vehicle collisions resulting in injury or death than either fire trucks or police cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Unrestrained occupants, particularly those riding in the patient-care compartment, are particularly vulnerable.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] When compared to civilian vehicles of similar size, one study found that on a per-accident basis, ambulance collisions tend to involve more people, and result in more injuries.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] An 11-year retrospective study concluded in 2001 found that although most fatal ambulance crashes in the United States occurred during emergency runs, they typically occurred on improved, straight, dry roads, during clear weather.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Furthermore, paramedics are also at risk in ambulances while helping patients, as 27 paramedics died during ambulance trips in the US between 1991 and 2006.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In addition to the equipment directly used for the treatment of patients, ambulances may be fitted with a range of additional equipment which is used in order to facilitate patient care.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In parts of the world that lack a high level of infrastructure, ambulances are designed to meet local conditions, being built using intermediate technology.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances can also be trailers, which are pulled by bicycles, motorcycles, tractors, or animals.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Animal-powered ambulances can be particularly useful in regions that are subject to flooding.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Motorcycles fitted with sidecars (or motorcycle ambulances) are also used, though they are subject to some of the same limitations as more traditional over-the-road ambulances.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The level of care provided by these ambulances varies between merely providing transport to a medical clinic to providing on-scene and continuing care during transport.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The design of intermediate technology ambulances must take into account not only the operation and maintenance of the ambulance, but its construction as well.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The robustness of the design becomes more important, as does the nature of the skills required to properly operate the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Cost-effectiveness can be a high priority.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Emergency ambulances are highly likely to be involved in hazardous situations, including incidents such as a road traffic collision, as these emergencies create people who are likely to be in need of treatment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] They are required to gain access to patients as quickly as possible, and in many countries, are given dispensation from obeying certain traffic laws.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] For instance, they may be able to run the red light or stop sign , or be permitted to break the speed limit.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Generally, the priority of the response to the call will be assigned by the dispatcher, but the priority of the return will be decided by the ambulance crew based on the severity of the patient's illness or injury.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Passive visual warnings are usually part of the design of the vehicle, and involve the use of high contrast patterns.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Older ambulances (and those in developing countries) are more likely to have their pattern painted on, whereas modern ambulances generally carry retro-reflective designs, which reflects light from car headlights or torches.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In addition to retro-reflective markings, some services now have the vehicles painted in a bright (sometimes fluorescent) yellow or orange for maximum visual impact, though classic white or red are also common.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Fire department-operated ambulances are often painted red to match the fire apparatuses.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Another passive marking form is the word *ambulance* (or local language variant) spelled out in reverse on the front of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] This enables drivers of other vehicles to more easily identify an approaching ambulance in their rear view mirrors.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances may display the name of their owner or operator, and an emergency telephone number for the ambulance service.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances may also carry an emblem (either as part of the passive warning markings or not), such as a Red Cross, Red Crescent or Red Crystal (collective known as the Protective Symbols).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These are symbols laid down by the Geneva Convention, and all countries signatory to it agree to restrict their use to either (1) Military Ambulances or (2) the national Red Cross or Red Crescent society.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Use by any other person, organization or agency is in breach of international law.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The protective symbols are designed to indicate to all people (especially combatants in the case of war) that the vehicle is neutral and is not to be fired upon, hence giving protection to the medics and their casualties, although this has not always been adhered to.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In Israel, Magen David Adom, the Red Cross member organization use a red Star of David, but this does not have recognition beyond Israeli borders, where they must use the Red Crystal.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The Star of Life is widely used, and was originally designed and governed by the U.S.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, because the Red Cross symbol is legally protected by both National and international law.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulance services with historical origins such as the Order of St John, the Order of Malta Ambulance Corps and Malteser International often use the Maltese cross to identify their ambulances.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] This is especially important in countries such as Australia, where St.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] John Ambulance operate one state and one territory ambulance service, and all of Australia's other ambulance services use variations on a red Maltese cross.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Fire service operated ambulances may display the Cross of St.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Florian (often incorrectly called a Maltese cross) as this cross is frequently used as a fire department logo (St.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Florian being the patron saint of firefighters).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The active visual warnings are usually in the form of flashing lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These flash in order to attract the attention of other road users as the ambulance approaches, or to provide warning to motorists approaching a stopped ambulance in a dangerous position on the road.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Common colours for ambulance warning beacons are blue, red, amber, and white (clear).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] However the colours may vary by country and sometimes by operator.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] There are several technologies in use to achieve the flashing effect.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These include flashing a light bulb or LED, flashing or rotating halogen, and strobe lights, which are usually brighter than incandescent lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Incandescent and LED lights may also be programmed to burn steadily, without flashing, which is required in some provinces.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These hidden lights may not be apparent until they are activated.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Additionally, some of the standard lights fitted to an ambulance (e.g. headlamps, tail lamps) may be programmed to flash.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Flashing headlights (typically the high beams, flashed alternately) are known as a wig-wag.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Additional white lights may be placed strategically around the vehicle to illuminate the area around it when it is dark, almost always at the rear for loading and unloading stretchers and often at the sides as well.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In areas very far North or South where there are times of year with long periods of darkness, additional driving lights at the front are often fitted as well to increase visibility for the driver.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In order to increase safety, it is best practice to have 360° coverage with the active warnings, improving the chance of the vehicle being seen from all sides.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In some countries, such as the United States, this may be mandatory.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The roof, front grille, sides and rear of the body, and front fenders are common places to mount emergency lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] A certain balance must be made when deciding on the number and location of lights: too few and the ambulance may not be noticed easily, too many and it becomes a massive distraction for other road users more than it is already, increasing the risk of local accidents.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In addition to visual warnings, ambulances can be fitted with **audible warnings**, sometimes known as sirens, which can alert people and vehicles to the presence of an ambulance before they can be seen.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The first audible warnings were mechanical bells, mounted to either the front or roof of the ambulance.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Most modern ambulances are now fitted with electronic sirens, producing a range of different noises which ambulance operators can use to attract more attention to themselves, particularly when proceeding through an intersection or in heavy traffic.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The speakers for modern sirens can be integral to the lightbar, or they may be hidden in or flush to the grill to reduce noise inside the ambulance that may interfere with patient care and radio communications.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulances can additionally be fitted with airhorn audible warnings to augment the effectiveness of the siren system, or may be fitted with extremely loud two-tone air horns as their primary siren.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] A recent development is the use of the RDS system of car radios.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The ambulance is fitted with a short range FM transmitter, set to RDS code 31, which interrupts the radio of all cars within range, in the manner of a traffic broadcast, but in such a way that the user of the receiving radio is unable to opt-out of the message (as with traffic broadcasts).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] This feature is built into every RDS radio for use in national emergency broadcast systems, but short-range units on emergency vehicles can prove an effective means of alerting traffic to their presence.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] It is, however, unlikely that this system could replace audible warnings, as it is unable to alert pedestrians, those not using a compatible radio or even have it turned off.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In the United States, the cost of an ambulance ride may be paid for from several sources, and this will depend on the local situation type of service being provided, by whom, and to whom.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] There are differing levels of qualification that the ambulance crew may hold, from holding no formal qualification to having a fully qualified doctor on board.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Most ambulance services require at least two crew members to be on every ambulance (one to drive, and one to attend the patient).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] It may be the case that only the attendant need be qualified, and the driver might have no medical training.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In some locations, an advanced life support ambulance may be crewed by one paramedic and one technician, or in countries like Australia advanced life support registered paramedics.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Military ambulances have historically included vehicles based on civilian designs and at times also included armored, but unarmed, vehicle ambulances based upon armoured personnel carriers (APCs).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In the Second World War vehicles such as the Hanomag Sd Kfz 251 half-track were pressed into service as ad hoc ambulances, and in more recent times purpose-built AFVs such as the U.S.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] M1133 medical evacuation vehicle serve the exclusive purpose of armored medical vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Civilian based designs may be painted in appropriate colors, depending on the operational requirements (i.e. camouflage for field use, white for United Nations peacekeeping, etc.).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] For example, the British Royal Army Medical Corps has a fleet of white ambulances, based on production trucks.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Military helicopters have also served both as ad hoc and purpose-built air ambulances since they are extremely useful for MEDEVAC.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In terms of equipment, military ambulances are barebones, often being nothing more than a box on wheels with racks to place manual stretchers, though for the operational conditions and level of care involved this is usually sufficient.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Since laws of war demand ambulances be marked with one of the emblems of the Red Cross not to mount offensive weapons, military ambulances are often unarmed.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] It is a generally accepted practice in most countries to classify the personnel attached to military vehicles marked as ambulances as non-combatants; however, this does not always exempt medical personnel from coming under fire – accidental or deliberate.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] As a result, medics and other medical personnel attached to military ambulances are usually put through basic military training, on the assumption that they may have to use a weapon.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The laws of war do allow non-combatant military personnel to carry individual weapons for protecting themselves and casualties.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] However, not all militaries exercise this right to their personnel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The Israeli Defense Forces modified a number of its Merkava main battle tanks with ambulance features in order to allow rescue operations to take place under heavy fire in urban warfare.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] The modifications were made following a failed rescue attempt in which Palestinian gunmen killed two soldiers who were providing aid for a Palestinian woman in Rafah.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Since M113 armored personnel carriers and regular up-armored ambulances are not sufficiently protected against anti-tank weapons and improvised explosive devices, it was decided to use the heavily armored Merkava tank.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Its rear door enables the evacuation of critically wounded soldiers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Israel did not remove the Merkava's weaponry, claiming that weapons were more effective protection than emblems since Palestinian militants would disregard any symbols of protection and fire at ambulances anyway.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Some navies operate ocean-going hospital ships to lend medical assistance in high casualty situations such as wars or natural disasters.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] These hospital ships fulfill the criteria of an ambulance (transporting the sick or injured), although the capabilities of a hospital ship are more on par with a Mobile Army Surgical Hospital.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] In line with the laws of war, these ships can display a prominent Red Cross or Red Crescent to confer protection under the appropriate Geneva Convention.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] However, this designation has not always protected hospital ships from enemy fire.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Ambulettes provide patient transport service for non-emergency situations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Scheduling is a major factor in their effective use.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] When an ambulance is retired, it may be donated or sold to another EMS provider or find their new usage in developing countries.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Alternately, it may be adapted into a storage and transport vehicle for crime scene identification equipment, a command post at community events, or support vehicle, such as a logistics unit.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Others are refurbished and resold, or may just have their emergency equipment removed to be sold to private businesses or individuals, who then can use them as small recreational vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] They may also have a perfectly serviceable body or vehicle (or both) separated from the other and reused.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Toronto City Council operates a "Caravan of Hope" project to give retired Toronto ambulances a second life by donating them to the people of El Salvador.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/ambulance] Since Ontario laws require ambulances to be retired after just four and a half years in service, the City of Toronto decommissions and auctions around 28 ambulances each year.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Many emergency vehicles have distinctive lighting equipment to warn drivers of their presence.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Early road vehicles used fuelled lamps before the availability of electric lighting.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] The first Ford Model T used carbide lamps for headlights and oil lamps for tail lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] It did not have all-electric lighting as a standard feature until several years after its introduction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Dynamos for automobile headlights were first fitted around 1908 and became commonplace in 1920s automobiles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Trafficators—signalling arms that flipped up, which later were lighted—were introduced in the early 1900s, and were actuated either mechanically or pneumatically.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Tail lights and brake lights were introduced around 1915, and by 1919, low-beam or dipped beam headlights were available.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Sealed beam headlights were introduced in 1936 and standardized as the only acceptable type in the US in 1940.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Self-cancelling turn signals were developed in 1940.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] By 1945, headlights and signal lights were integrated into the body styling.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Halogen headlights were developed in Europe in 1960.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] High-intensity discharge (HID) headlights were produced starting in 1991.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] In 1993, the first LED tail lights were installed on mass-production automobiles, with LED headlights subsequently being introduced in the 2000s as more powerful LEDs became available.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] The colour of light emitted by vehicle lights is largely standardized by established conventions, first codified in the 1949 Geneva Convention on Road Traffic and later specified in the 1968 United Nations Vienna Convention on Road Traffic.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] With some regional exceptions, lights facing rearward must emit red light, side-facing lights and all turn signals must emit amber light, and lights facing forward must emit white or selective yellow light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] No other colours are permitted except on emergency vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Vehicle lighting colour specifications can differ somewhat in countries that have not signed the 1949 and/or 1968 Conventions; examples include turn signals and side marker lights in North America, as described in those lights' sections later in this article.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Forward illumination is provided by high- ("main", "full", "driving") and low- ("dip", "dipped", "passing") beam headlights, which may be augmented by auxiliary fog lights, driving lights, or cornering lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Low beam (also called dipped beam, passing beam, or meeting beam) headlights provide adequate forward and lateral illumination without dazzling other road users with excessive glare.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] This beam is specified for use whenever other vehicles are present ahead.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE regulations for dipped beam headlights specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is flat and low, while the half of the beam closest to the outside of the road slopes up and towards the near side of the roadway.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] This permits a functional compromise where it is possible to substantially prevent glare for oncoming drivers, while still allowing adequate illumination for drivers to see pedestrians, road signs, hazards, etc. on their side of the road.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] The United States and Canada use proprietary FMVSS / CMVSS standards instead of UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] These standards contain regulations for dipped beam headlights that also specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is also flat and low, but not as low as prescribed in UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] The half of the beam closest to the outside of the road is also flat, but higher than the half closest to oncoming vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] This results in substantially increased glare for oncoming drivers and also poorer illumination of the near side of the roadway in comparison to headlights conforming to UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] High beam (also called main beam, driving beam, or full beam) headlights provide an intense, centre-weighted distribution of light with no particular glare control.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Therefore, they are only suitable for use when alone on the road, as the glare they produce will dazzle other drivers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE Regulations permit higher-intensity high-beam headlights than allowed under U.S. and Canadian FMVSS / CMVSS standards.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Auxiliary high beam lights may be fitted to provide high-intensity light to enable the driver to see at longer range than the vehicle's high beam headlights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Such lights are most notably fitted on rally cars, and are occasionally fitted to production vehicles derived from or imitating such cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] They are common in countries with large stretches of unlit roads, or in regions such as the Nordic countries that receive fewer daylight hours during winter.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] "Driving light" is a term hailing from the early days of night time driving, when it was relatively rare to encounter an opposing vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Only on occasions when opposing drivers passed each other would the low (dipped or "passing") beam be used.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] The high beam was therefore known as the "driving beam", and this terminology is still found in international UN Regulations, which do not distinguish between a vehicle's primary (mandatory) and auxiliary (optional) upper/driving beam lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] The "driving light" term has been supplanted in US regulations by the functionally descriptive term "auxiliary high-beam light".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Many countries regulate the installation and use of driving lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] For example, in Russia, each vehicle may have no more than three pairs of driving lights (including the original lights), and in Paraguay, auxiliary driving lights must be off and covered with opaque material when the vehicle is operated in urban areas.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Front fog lights provide a wide, bar-shaped beam of light with a sharp cutoff at the top, and are generally aimed and mounted low.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] They may produce white or selective yellow light, and were designed for use at low speed to increase the illumination directed towards the road surface and verges in conditions of poor visibility due to fog, dust or snow.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] They are sometimes used in place of dipped-beam headlights, reducing glare from fog or falling snow, although the legality of using front fog lights without low-beam headlights varies by jurisdiction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] In most countries, weather conditions rarely necessitate the use of front fog lights and there is no legal requirement for them, so their primary purpose is frequently cosmetic.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] They are often available as optional extras or only on higher trim levels of many cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Since as early as the 2020s, several car manufacturers have noticeably omitted the front fog lights from many of their latest models, as more recent high-tech lighting technologies such as daytime running lamps (DRLs) and LEDs connected to automatic high-beam systems negate the use of fog lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] However, some manufacturers who still offer fog lights as standard equipment in certain model trims have diversified its use to function also as an automatic lighting delay for vehicles, to light up surroundings and roadside curbs after being parked.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] An SAE study has shown that in the United States, more people inappropriately use their fog lights in dry weather than use them properly in poor weather.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] The respective purposes of front fog lights and driving lights are often confused, due in part to the misconception that fog lights are always selective yellow, while any auxiliary light that makes white light is a driving light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Automakers and aftermarket parts and accessories suppliers frequently refer interchangeably to "fog lights" and "driving lights" (or "fog/driving lights").
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] On some models, cornering lights provide steady-intensity white light for lateral illumination in the direction of an intended turn or lane change.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] They are generally actuated in conjunction with the turn signals, and they may be wired to also illuminate when the vehicle is shifted into reverse gear.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Some modern vehicles activate the cornering light on one or the other side when the steering wheel input reaches a predetermined angle in that direction, regardless of whether a turn signal has been activated.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] American technical standards contain provisions for front cornering lights as well as rear cornering lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Cornering lights have traditionally been prohibited under international UN Regulations, though provisions have recently been made to allow them as long as they are only operable when the vehicle is travelling at less than 40 kilometres per hour (about 25 mph).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p01] Police cars, emergency vehicles, and vehicles competing in road rallies are sometimes equipped with an auxiliary spotlight, sometimes called an "alley light", in a swivel-mounted housing attached to one or both A-pillars, aimed by a handle protruding through the pillar into the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity devices are lights and reflectors that are intended to make a vehicle more conspicuous and visible with respect to its presence, position, direction of travel, change in direction, or deceleration.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Such lights may light steadily, blink, or flash, depending on their intended and regulated function.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Most must be fitted in pairs—one left and one right—though some vehicles have multiple pairs (such as two left and two right stop lights) and/or redundant light sources (such as one left and one right stop light, each containing two bulbs).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Front position lights (known as parking lights in North America and front sidelights in the UK) provide nighttime standing-vehicle conspicuity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They are designed to use little electricity so they can be left on when parked for prolonged periods of time.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Despite the UK term, these are not the same as the side marker lights described below.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The front position lights on any vehicle must emit white light, with the exception of motorcycles, which may have amber front position lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, Canada, Mexico, Iceland, Japan, New Zealand, and Australia (only if combined with a side marker), South Korea, North Korea, Vietnam, China, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, and much of the Middle East, they may emit amber light on any vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The "city light" terminology for front position lights derives from the practice, formerly adhered to in cities like Moscow, London and Paris, of driving at night in urban areas using these low-intensity lights rather than the vehicle's headlights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In Germany, the StVZO (Road Traffic Licensing Regulations) calls for a different function provided by these lights: with the vehicle's ignition switched off, the operator may activate a low-intensity white light at the front and red light at the rear on either the left or right side.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This function is used when parking in narrow unlit streets to provide parked-vehicle conspicuity to approaching drivers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This function, which is optional under UN and US regulations, is served passively in the United States by mandatory side marker retroreflectors.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some countries permit or require vehicles to be equipped with daytime running lights (DRLs).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the regulations of the country for which the vehicle is built, these may be functionally dedicated lights, or the function may be provided by the low beam or high beam headlights, the front turn signals, or the front fog lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Passenger cars and small delivery vans first type approved to UN Regulation 48 on or after 7 February 2011, and large vehicles (trucks and buses) type approved since August 2012, must be equipped with DRLs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Functional piggybacking, such as using the headlights, front turn signals, or fog lights as DRLs, is not permitted; the EU Directive requires functionally specific daytime running lights compliant with UN Regulation 87 and mounted to the vehicle in accord with UN Regulation 48.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Prior to the DRL mandate, countries requiring daytime lights permitted low beam headlights to provide that function.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] National regulations in Canada, Sweden, Norway, Slovenia, Finland, Iceland, and Denmark require hardwired automatic DRL systems of varying specification.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] DRLs are permitted in many countries where they are not required, but prohibited in other countries not requiring them.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Front, side, and rear position lights are permitted, required, or forbidden to illuminate in combination with daytime running lights, depending on the jurisdiction and the DRL implementation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Likewise, according to jurisdictional regulations, DRLs mounted within a certain distance of turn signals are permitted or required to extinguish or dim down to parking light intensity individually when the adjacent turn signal is operating.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 87 stipulates that DRLs must emit white light with an intensity of at least 400 candela on axis and no more than 1200 candela in any direction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, daytime running lights may emit either amber or white light, and may produce up to 7,000 candela.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This has provoked a large number of complaints about glare.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] UK regulations briefly required vehicles first used on or after 1 April 1987 to be equipped with a "dim-dip" device or special low-intensity running lights, except such vehicles as complying fully with UN Regulation 48 regarding the installation of lighting equipment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] A dim-dip device operates the dipped beam headlights at between 10% and 20% of normal low-beam intensity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Running lights permitted as an alternative to dim-dip were required to emit at least 200 candela straight ahead, and no more than 800 candela in any direction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In practice, most vehicles were equipped with the dim-dip option rather than dedicated running lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The dim-dip systems were not intended for daytime use as DRLs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather, they operated if the engine was running *and* the driver switched on the position lights (called sidelights in the UK).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The UK was the only country to require such dim-dip systems, though vehicles so equipped were sold in other Commonwealth countries with left-hand traffic.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1988, the European Commission successfully prosecuted the UK government in the European Court of Justice, arguing that the UK requirement for dim-dip was illegal under EC directives prohibiting member states from enacting vehicle lighting requirements not contained in pan-European EC directives.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] As a result, the UK requirement for dim-dip was quashed.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Nevertheless, dim-dip systems remain permitted, and while such systems are not presently as common as they once were, dim-dip functionality was fitted on many new cars well into the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States, amber front and red rear side marker lights and retroreflectors are required.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The law initially required lights *or* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1968.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This was amended to require lights *and* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1970.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These side-facing devices make the vehicle's presence, position and direction of travel clearly visible from oblique angles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The lights are wired to illuminate whenever the vehicles' parking lights and tail lights are on, including when the headlights are being used.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Front amber side markers in the United States may be wired to flash in synchronous phase or opposite-phase with the turn signals; nevertheless, they are not required to flash at all.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Side markers are permitted but not required on cars and light passenger vehicles outside the United States and Canada.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These were sometimes used in tandem with fender lights during the same time period, when fenders were separate from the body and only covered the wheels.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They are activated by the driver on one side of the vehicle at a time to advertise intent to turn or change lanes towards that side, or used simultaneously as a hazard warning signal to warn other drivers of a vehicle parked on the road (see below).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] For many years, turn signals' on-off operation was activated by a thermal flasher unit which used a heating element, leaf spring, and a bimetallic strip.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] When activated by the stalk switch on the steering column, the signal lights and heating element turned on.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The heat caused the bimetallic strip to bend such that it threw the leaf spring over centre, opening the circuit and breaking power to the heating element and the signal lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] When the bimetallic strip cooled down, it would pull the leaf spring back over centre in the other direction, closing the contacts and again sending power to the lights and heating element.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The cycle would repeat until the power to the thermal flasher was switched off by the stalk switch.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Thermal flashers gradually gave way to electromechanical relays; one of many control strategies with relay-type flashers is to use a relaxation oscillator chip to generate square waves to the relay coil, causing the relay contacts to open and close.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern cars now use a relaxation oscillator and solid-state relay built into the body control module to flash the lights, and use speakers to produce the distinctive clicking sound associated with turn signals, which was previously made by a relay or the leaf spring in a thermal flasher.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] If the stalk switch is not moved beyond the fixed left/right position and allowed to flip back, the control module will only flash the lights three times.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Electric turn signal lights date from as early as 1907.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1908, Alfredo Barrachini in Rome added electric lights inside the arms that turned on as they extended, but operation was still by a cable system.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] An early patent for a new style of turn signal was issued in 1909 to a British man named Percy Douglas-Hamilton, who came up with a system that used a hand on each side of the car, which could be illuminated to indicate a coming turn.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Silent film star Florence Lawrence is also credited with introducing an innovative version of the signalling arm in 1914, a predecessor to the modern turn signal, and a mechanical brake signal.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] She did not patent these inventions, however, and received no credit or profit from them.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Possibly the first factory installation of illuminated turn signals was on the Talbot 105 (as well as the 75 and 95), which used them at the front as well as at the rear from 1932 until 1935.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The modern flashing turn signal was patented in 1938, and shortly after, most major automobile manufacturers offered this optional feature before it became mandatory in 1967.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] As of 2013, most countries require turn signals on all new vehicles that are driven on public roadways.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Alternative systems of hand signals were used earlier and remain common for bicycles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Hand signals are also sometimes used when regular vehicle lights are malfunctioning or for older vehicles without turn signals.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some cars from about 1900 to through 1966 used retractable semaphores called trafficators rather than flashing lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They were commonly mounted high up behind the front doors and swung out to a horizontal position.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They were fragile and could be easily broken off, and also had a tendency to stick in the closed or open position.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They could be fitted with a fixed or flashing light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] After turn signals were introduced regulations were brought in requiring them and laying out specifications that had to be met.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In most countries, cars must be equipped with side-mounted turn signal repeaters to make the turn indication visible laterally (i.e. to the sides of the vehicle) rather than just to the front and rear of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These are permitted, but not required in the United States and Canada.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] As an alternative in both the United States and Canada, the front amber side marker lights may be wired to flash with the turn signals, but this is not mandatory.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Mercedes-Benz introduced side turn signal repeaters integrated into the side-view mirrors in 1998, starting with its facelifted E-Class (W210).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Since then, many automakers have been incorporating side turn signal devices into the mirror housings rather than mounting them on the vehicle's fenders.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some evidence suggests that mirror-mounted turn signals may be more effective than fender-mounted ones.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are required to blink on and off, or "flash", at a steady rate of between 60 and 120 pulses per minute (1–2 Hz).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations require that all turn signals flash in simultaneous phase; US regulations permit side marker lights wired for side turn signal functionality to flash in opposite-phase.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] An audio and/or visual tell-tale indicator is required, to advise the driver when the turn signals are activated and operating.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This usually takes the form of one green light on the dashboard on cars from the 1950s or older, or two green indicator lights on cars from the 1960s to the present, and a rhythmic ticking sound generated electromechanically or electronically by the flasher.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] It is also required that the vehicle operator be alerted by much faster- or slower-than-normal flashing in the event a turn signal light fails.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are, in almost every case, activated by a horizontal stalk protruding from the side of the steering column, though on some vehicles it protrudes from the dashboard.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The driver raises or lowers the outboard end of the stalk in accord with the clockwise or anticlockwise direction the steering wheel is about to be turned.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In left-hand drive vehicles, the turn indicator stalk is usually located to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In right-hand-drive vehicles, there is less consistency; it may be located to the left or to the right of the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations do not specify a mandatory location for the turn signal control, only that it be visible and operable by the driver, and—at least in North America—that it be labelled with a specific symbol if it is not located on the left side of the steering column.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The international UN Regulations do not include analogous specifications.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Virtually all vehicles (except many motorcycles and commercial semi-tractors) have a turn indicator self-cancelling feature that returns the lever to the neutral (no signal) position as the steering wheel approaches the straight-ahead position after a turn has been made.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Beginning in the late 1960s, using the direction-indicator lights to signal for a lane change was facilitated by the addition of a spring-loaded momentary signal-on position just shy of the left and right detents.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The signal operates for however long the driver holds the lever partway towards the left or right turn signal detent.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have an automatic lane-change indication feature; tapping the lever partway towards the left or right signal position and immediately releasing it causes the applicable turn indicators to flash three to five times.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some transit buses, such as those in New York, have turn signals activated by floor-mounted momentary-contact footswitches on the floor near the driver's left foot (on left-hand drive buses).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The foot-activated signals allow bus drivers to keep both hands on the steering wheel while watching the road and scanning for passengers as they approach a bus stop.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] New York City Transit bus drivers, among others, are trained to step continuously on the right directional switch while servicing a bus stop, to signal other road users they are intentionally dwelling at the stop, allowing following buses to skip that stop.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This method of signalling requires no special arrangements for self-cancellation or passing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Sequential turn signals are a feature on some cars, wherein the turn signal function is provided by multiple lit elements that illuminate sequentially rather than simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The visual effect is one of outward motion in the direction of the intended turn or lane change.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The earlier, fitted to the 1965 through 1968 Ford-built cars and the 1971–1972 Nissan Cedric, employed an electric motor driving, through reduction gearing, a set of three slow-turning cams.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These cams would actuate switches to turn on the lights in sequence.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Later Ford cars and the 1969 Imperial used a transistorised control module with no moving parts to wear, break, or go out of adjustment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] FMVSS 108 has been officially interpreted as requiring all light sources in an active turn signal to illuminate simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles, such as the 2010 and later Ford Mustang, are designed such that the first lit segment of the multi-unit light is considered as the official turn signal, with the segments illuminated afterward considered as auxiliary lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Other US vehicles with sequential turn signals comply by illuminating all elements of the turn signal simultaneously, before sequentially turning them off.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Until the early 1960s, most front turn signals worldwide emitted white light and most rear turn signals emitted red light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Currently, most countries outside the United States and Canada require that all front, side and rear turn signals produce amber light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In Belgium, Brazil, Canada, the GCC countries, Israel, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Switzerland, and the US, the rear signals may be amber or red.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Additionally, red turn signals can also be found in countries with trade agreements with the US such as Mexico and South Korea, and New Zealand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of red rear turn signals have claimed that they are less costly to manufacture, and automakers use the turn signal colour as a styling element to differentiate vehicles of different model years.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of amber rear turn signals say they are more easily discernible as turn signals.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] It has been recognised since the 1960s that amber turn signals are more quickly spotted than red ones.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] There is some evidence that turn signals with colourless clear lenses and amber bulbs may be less conspicuous in bright sunlight than those with amber lenses and colourless bulbs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The amber bulbs commonly used in turn signals with colourless lenses are no longer made with cadmium glass, since various regulations worldwide, including the European RoHS directive, banned cadmium because of its toxicity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Amber glass made without cadmium is relatively costly, so most amber bulbs are now made with clear glass dipped in an amber coating.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] With accumulated heat-cool cycles, though, some of these coatings may flake off the bulb glass, or the colour may fade.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This causes the turn signal to emit white light rather than the required amber light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The international regulation on motor vehicle bulbs requires manufacturers to test bulbs for colour endurance.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] However, no test protocol or colour durability requirement is specified.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Discussion is ongoing within the *Groupe des Rapporteurs d'Éclairage*, the UNECE working group on vehicular lighting regulation, to develop and implement a colour durability standard.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather than using an amber bulb, some signal lights contain an inner amber plastic enclosure between a colourless bulb and the colourless outer lens or by using integrated amber LEDs in a colourless enclosure which produces less heat.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity for the rear of a vehicle is provided by rear position lights (also called tail lights).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These are required to produce only red light and to be wired such that they are lit whenever the front position lights are lit, including when the headlights are on.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear position lights may be combined with the vehicle's stop lights or be separate from them.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In combined-function installations, the lights produce brighter red light as stop lights and dimmer red light as rear position lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide stipulate minimum intensity ratios between the bright (stop) and dim (position) modes, so that a vehicle displaying rear position lights will not be mistakenly interpreted as showing stop lights and vice versa.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Red steadily lit rear lights, brighter than the rear position lights, are activated when the driver applies the vehicle's brakes and warn vehicles behind to prepare to stop.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These are formally called "stop lamps" in technical standards and regulations and in the Vienna Convention on Road Traffic, though they are often informally called brake lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They are required to be fitted in multiples of two, symmetrically at the left and right edges of the rear of every vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] 7 specify a range of acceptable intensity for a stop light of 60 to 185 candela.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where the UN regulations are not recognised, the acceptable range for a single-compartment stop light is 80 to 300 candela.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and Canada since 1986, in Australia and New Zealand since 1990, and in Europe and other countries applying UN Regulation 48 since 1998, a central stop (brake) light mounted higher than the vehicle's left and right stop lights is also required.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The so-called "centre high mount stop lamp", or **CHMSL** (pronounced /ˈtʃɪmzəl/), is sometimes informally called the "centre brake light", the "third brake light", the "eye-level brake light", the "safety brake light", or the "high-level brake light".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL may use one or more filament bulbs or LEDs, or a strip of neon tubing as its light source.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is intended to provide a warning to drivers whose view of the vehicle's left and right stop lights is blocked by interceding vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] It also provides a redundant stop light signal in the event of a stop light malfunction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where rear turn signals are permitted to emit red light, the CHMSL also helps to differentiate brake lights from rear position lights and turn signal lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] On passenger cars, the CHMSL may be placed above the back glass, affixed to the vehicle's interior just inside the back glass, or integrated into the vehicle's deck lid or into a spoiler.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Other specialised fitments are sometimes seen; the Jeep Wrangler and Land Rover Freelander have the CHMSL on a stalk fixed to the spare wheel carrier.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Trucks, vans, and commercial vehicles sometimes have the CHMSL mounted to the trailing edge of the vehicle's roof.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is required by regulations worldwide to be centred laterally on the vehicle, though UN Regulation 48 permits lateral offset of up to 15 cm if the vehicle's lateral centre is not coincident with a fixed body panel, but instead separates movable components such as doors.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Such an offset can be seen on the third-generation Renault Master and first-generation Ford Transit Connect vans.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The height of the CHMSL is also regulated, both in absolute terms and with respect to the mounting height of the vehicle's conventional left and right stop lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the left and right lights' height, the lower edge of the CHMSL may be just above the left and right lights' upper edge.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1952 Volkswagen Bus was equipped with only one stop light, mounted centrally and higher than the left and right rear lights, which did not produce a stop light function.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1968–1971 Ford Thunderbird could be ordered with optional supplemental high-mounted stop and turn signal lights integrated into the left and right interior trim surrounding the rear glass.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The Oldsmobile Toronado (from 1971 to 1978) and the Buick Riviera (from 1974 to 1976) had similar dual high-mounted supplemental stop/turn lights as standard equipment; these were located on the outside of the vehicle below the bottom of the rear glass.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of configuration was not widely adopted at the time.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Car and lighting manufacturers in Germany experimented with dual high-mount supplemental stop lights in the early 1980s, but this effort, too, failed to gain wide popular or regulatory support.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Effective with the 1986 model year, the United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada mandated that all new passenger cars come equipped with a CHMSL.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The requirement was extended to light trucks and vans for the 1994 model year.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Early studies involving taxicabs and other fleet vehicles found that a third high-level stop light reduced rear-end collisions by about 50%.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Once the novelty effect wore off as most vehicles on the road came to be equipped with a CHMSL, the crash-avoidance benefit declined.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] However, said benefit has not declined to zero, and a CHMSL has become so inexpensive to incorporate into a vehicle that it remains a cost-effective collision avoidance feature even at the long-term enduring crash-reduction benefit of 4.3%.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] A NHTSA report suggests that a vehicle equipped with a CHMSL has 23.7% less risk to be involved as a lead vehicle in a chain collision and 16.0% less risk to be involved as a middle vehicle in such a collision.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency stop signalling is a lighting function wherein the vehicle's stop (brake) lights and/or hazard/turn indicators flash in phase at 3 to 5 Hz under heavy or urgent braking.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The emergency stop signal is automatically activated if the vehicle speed is greater than 50 km/h (31 mph) and the emergency braking logic defined by regulation No.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In February 2019, members of the European Parliament approved rules making emergency stop signals mandatory on new vehicles sold in the European Union.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Toyota, Mercedes-Benz, Volvo and BMW were among the earlier automakers to begin equipping vehicles with ESS.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2013, Kia introduced the concept on some of their Australian-market models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Other methods of severe braking indication have also been implemented; some Volvo models make the stop lights brighter, and some BMWs have "Adaptive Brake Lights" that effectively increase the size of the stop lights under severe braking by illuminating them at brighter-than-normal intensity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] As long as the brighter-than-normal stop lights are within the regulated maximum intensity for stop lights in general, this kind of implementation does not require specific regulatory approval, since the stop lights continue to operate in accord with general stop light regulations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The idea behind such emergency braking indicator systems is to catch following drivers' attention with increased urgency.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] However, there remains considerable debate over whether the system offers a measurable increase in safety.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] To date, studies of vehicles with ESS have not shown significant improvement.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The systems used by BMW, Volvo, and Mercedes differ not only in operational mode (growing vs. intensifying vs. flashing, respectively), but also in such parameters as the deceleration threshold of activation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Data is being collected and analyzed in an effort to determine how such a system might be implemented to maximize a safety benefit, if such a benefit can be realized with visual emergency braking displays.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] An experimental study at the University of Toronto has tested stop lights which gradually and continuously grow in illuminated area with increasing braking.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The ESS is not expensive because it reuses existing warning and stop signals.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] One potential problem with flashing stop lights in the United States and Canada is regulations that permit flashing stop lights to be used as rear turn signal and hazard lights, in lieu of separate dedicated lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In Europe and other countries adhering to UN Regulation 48, vehicles must be equipped with one or two bright red "rear fog lamps", which serve as high-intensity rear position lights to be activated in poor visibility conditions to make the vehicle more visible from the rear.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The allowable range of intensity for a rear fog light is 150 to 300 candela, within the range of a US stop light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear fog lights are not required equipment in the US, but they are permitted, and they are found almost exclusively on European-brand vehicles in North America.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Audi, Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz, Mini, Land Rover, Porsche, Saab, and Volvo provide functional rear fog lights on their North American models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles from non-European brands which are adaptions of European-market offerings, such as the first-generation Ford Transit Connect, have come standard with rear fog lights, or vehicles with European-market counterparts, such as the second generation Chrysler 300, have an option for them.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The second generation Oldsmobile Aurora also had dual rear fog lights installed in the rear bumper as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Most jurisdictions permit rear fog lights to be installed either singly or in pairs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] If a single rear fog is fitted, most jurisdictions require it to be located at or to the driver's side of the vehicle's centreline—whichever side is the prevailing driver's side in the country in which the vehicle is registered.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This is to maximise the sight line of following drivers to the rear fog light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In many cases, a single reversing light is mounted on the passenger side of the vehicle, positionally symmetrical with the rear fog.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] If two rear fog lights are fitted, they must be symmetrical with respect to the vehicle's centreline.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of twin rear fog lights say two lights provide vehicle distance information not available from a single light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of the single rear fog light say dual rear fog lights closely mimic the appearance of illuminated stop lights (which are mandatorily installed in pairs), reducing the conspicuity of the stop lights' message when the rear fogs are activated.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] To provide some safeguard against rear fog lights being confused with stop lights, UN Regulation 48 requires a separation of at least 10 cm between the closest illuminated edges of any stop light and any rear fog light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] To warn adjacent vehicle operators and pedestrians of a vehicle's rearward motion, and to provide illumination to the rear when reversing, each vehicle must be equipped with one or two rear-mounted, rear-facing reversing (or "backup") lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Reversing lights are required to produce white light by US and international UN regulations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] However, some countries have at various times permitted amber reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In Australia and New Zealand, for example, vehicle manufacturers were faced with the task of localizing American cars originally equipped with combination red brake/turn signal lights and white reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Both countries now require white reversing lights, and the combination amber turn/reverse light is no longer permitted on new vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The US state of Washington currently permits reversing lights to emit white or amber light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some car models, such as some Saabs have white reversing lights in the front turn indicators that switch on with the rear reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The rear registration plate is illuminated either by a single or a pair of yellow or white light(s), affixed within the indentation of the trunk or bumper.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] It is designed to light the surface of the plate without creating light directly visible to the rear of the vehicle, and must be illuminated whenever the position lights are lit.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Large vehicles such as trucks and buses are in many cases required to carry additional lighting devices beyond those required on passenger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The specific requirements vary according to the regulations in force where the vehicle is registered.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US and Canada, vehicles over 80 inches (2.032 m) wide must be equipped with three amber front and three red rear identification lights spaced 6–12 inches (15–30 cm) apart at the centre of the front and rear of the vehicle, as high as practicable.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The front identification lights are typically mounted atop the cab of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The purpose of these lights is to alert other drivers to the presence of a wide (and usually tall) vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 48 requires vehicles exceeding 2.10 metres (83 in) in width to be equipped with white front and red rear end-outline marker lights on both the left and right, which, like North American identification lights, are intended to indicate a vehicle's overall width and height.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The front clearance lights may be amber in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] US and Canadian regulations require large vehicles to be equipped with amber side marker lights and reflectors mounted midway between the front and rear side markers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Australian Design Rule 45/01 provides for side marker lights on trucks and other large vehicles producing amber light to the front and red to the rear with no requirement to emit light to the side.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Until about the 1970s in France, Spain, Morocco, and possibly other countries, many commercial vehicles and some Soviet Sovtransavto road trains had a green light mounted on the rear offside.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This could be operated by the driver to indicate that it was safe for the following vehicle to overtake.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The hazard warning signal (sometimes called "hazard warning flashers", "hazard warning lights", "emergency lights", "4-way flashers", "hazards", or "flashers") is provided by flashing all of a vehicle's left and right turn signals simultaneously and in phase.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Hazard warning signals first appeared as aftermarket accessories in the early 1950s; by the late 1960s, regulations around the world came to require all new vehicles to be so equipped.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Operation of the warning signals must be from a control independent of the turn signal control, and an audiovisual tell-tale must be provided to the driver.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In most vehicles, the hazard warning signals can be switched on and off with a physical push-button, which is typically marked with a triangular symbol, symbolizing a warning triangle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with separate left and right green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, both left and right indicators may flash to provide a visual indication of the hazard flashers' operation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with a single green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, a separate red tell-tale must be provided for hazard flasher indication.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Because the hazard flasher function operates the vehicle's left and right turn signals, a left or a right turn signal function may not be provided while the hazard flashers are operating.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Apart from its use as emergency lighting, a single flash of the hazard lights is used to show gratitude to yielding drivers in several countries.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] However, in the United Kingdom, they must not be used except to warn others of either a temporary obstruction when the vehicle is stationary or a hazard ahead on a dual carriageway with a speed limit of at least 50 mph.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] "Retroreflectors" (also called "reflex reflectors") produce no light of their own, but rather reflect incident light towards its source, such as another driver's headlights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They are regulated as automotive lighting devices, and specified to account for the separation between a vehicle's headlights and its driver's eyes.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Thus, vehicles can remain conspicuous even with their lights off.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide require all vehicles and trailers to be equipped with rear-facing red retroreflectors; in countries where UN Regulation No.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] 48 is applied, these must be triangular on trailers and non-triangular on vehicles other than trailers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Since 1968, US regulations also require side-facing retroreflectors, amber in front and red in the rear.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Sweden, South Africa, and other countries have at various times required white front-facing retroreflectors.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations explicitly permit vehicle signal lights with intensity automatically increased during bright daylight hours when sunlight reduces the effectiveness of the stop lights, and automatically decreased during hours of darkness when glare could be a concern.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations in the US and by the UN contain provisions for determining the minimum and maximum acceptable intensity for lights that contain more than a single light source.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some jurisdictions, such as the US states of Washington, Oregon and Idaho, permit vehicles to be equipped with auxiliary rear signal systems displaying a green light when the accelerator is depressed, yellow light when the vehicle is coasting, and red light when the brake is depressed.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Such systems have in the past been sold as aftermarket accessories, but are today seldom seen in traffic.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Since the late 1960s, there have been proposals to introduce a front-mounted brake light, where green or blue lights would indicate to pedestrians at crossings that an approaching vehicle is slowing down.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] A small subjective survey was undertaken in the US in 1971.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2014, the idea was suggested by Slovak Lubomír Marjak (of manufacturing company Lumaco, which makes front brake lights) to German EU parliamentarian Dieter-Lebrecht Koch.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Field tests were done in Germany in 2017, as well as in Slovakia in 2022 and 2023.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Expert analysts have found severe flaws in these tests and the accompanying safety claims.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The only production car to feature a built-in front brake light (as of 2023) was the Bricklin SV-1 of 1974.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, among other bodies, has commissioned studies of vehicle signal systems and configurations to determine the most promising avenues and best practices for enhanced crash avoidance via optimized vehicle conspicuity and signal lighting systems.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Most cars have at least one "dome light" (or "courtesy light") located in or near the ceiling of the passenger compartment, to provide illumination by which to fasten seatbelts and enter or exit the car.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These often have an option to automatically switch on when the front (or any) passenger doors are opened.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Many vehicles have expanded this feature, causing the overhead interior light to remain on after all doors are closed, allowing passengers to fasten seat belts with added illumination.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The extended lighting cycle usually ends when the vehicle's ignition has begun, or a gradual reduction in light emitted after a couple of minutes if the car is not started, called "theater" lighting.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Interior lighting has been added on some vehicles at the bottom edge of the dashboard, illuminating the floor for front passengers, or underneath the front seats at the rear, illuminating the floor for rear passengers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of convenience lighting approach is also sometimes used to illuminate interior or exterior door handles, exterior step running boards, or electric window switches.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] LED light sources appear increasingly as interior convenience lights in various locations, especially with finely focused lighting on console control surfaces and in cabin storage areas.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Map lights are aimed at specific passenger positions and allow for reading without glare distraction to the driver.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have "approach lighting" or "puddle lights" (lights that illuminate the ground outside the doors) in the exterior mirrors or lower edges of the doors, as well as interior lighting activated via key fob.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Many cars have lights in the trunk, the engine compartment, the glove box, and other storage compartments.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern pickup trucks usually have one or more white cargo lights that illuminate the bed of the truck, often controlled in conjunction with the interior dome lighting.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Most gauges and controls on a dashboard in modern vehicles are illuminated when the headlights are turned on, and the intensity of light can be adjusted by the driver for comfort.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Saab automobiles, for example, have an aircraft-style "night panel" function that shuts off all interior illumination save for the speedometer (unless attention is called to a critical situation on another gauge) to improve the driver's night vision.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency vehicles such as fire engines, ambulances, police cars, snow-removal vehicles and tow trucks are usually equipped with intense warning lights of particular colours.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] These may be motorised rotating beacons, xenon strobes, or arrays of LEDs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] The prescribed colours differ by jurisdiction; in most countries, blue and red special warning lights are used on police, fire, and medical-emergency vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and some other jurisdictions, amber lights are for tow trucks, private security personnel, construction vehicles, and other nonofficial special-service vehicles, while volunteer firefighters use red, blue, or green, depending on jurisdiction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US it is a violation of the DOT (Department of Transportation) Uniform Vehicle Code for any non-emergency vehicle (Police/Fire/Ambulance) to operate forward-facing red lights of any kind.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Some US states allow emergency vehicles to have blue lights that can be turned on to warn drivers of an emergency vehicle in action; blue and red lights can be combined, forward- and/or rear-facing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] In the UK, doctors may use green warning lights; although these do not allow the user to claim any exemption from road traffic regulations (compared to the blue lights used by statutory emergency services when responding to calls).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Special warning lights, usually amber, are also sometimes mounted on slow or wide vehicles such as mobile cranes, excavators, tractors, and even mobility scooters in certain conditions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Standard taxicabs for street hire are distinguished by special lights affixed to the vehicle's roof in accordance with local regulations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] They may have an illuminated "Taxi" sign, a light to signal that they are ready to take passengers, or off duty, or an emergency panic light the driver can activate in the event of a robbery to alert passersby to call the police.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on local regulations, the "Taxi" sign may also be required to display a number identifying the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The incandescent light bulb was for a long time the only light source used in automotive lighting.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Incandescent bulbs are still commonly used in turn signals to stop hyper-flashing of the turn signal flashers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Standardized type numbers are used by manufacturers to identify bulbs with the same specifications.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Bases may be bayonet-type with one or two contacts, plastic or glass wedges, or dual wire loops or ferrules used on tubular "festoon" lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Screw-base lights are never used in automobile applications due to their loosening under vibration.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Signal lights with internal or external coloured lenses use colourless bulbs; conversely, lights with colourless lenses may use red or amber bulbs to provide light of the required colours for the various functions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Tungsten-halogen lights are a very common light source for headlights and other forward illumination functions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Some recent vehicles use small halogen bulbs for exterior signalling and marking functions, as well.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The first halogen light approved for automotive use was the H1, which used 55 watts producing 1500 lumens and was introduced in Europe in 1962.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Since 1993, light-emitting diodes (LEDs) have increasingly been used in automotive lighting.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] They offer a very long service life, extreme vibration resistance, high colour durability, high efficiency (lumen/Watt) and can benefit from considerably more compact packaging compared to most bulb-type assemblies.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs also offer a potential safety benefit when employed in stop lights; when power is applied, they rise to full intensity approximately 250 milliseconds (¼ second) faster than incandescent bulbs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] This effectively instant rise time theoretically provides following drivers more time to react to the stop light signal, but has not been shown to make cars with LED stop lights less likely to be struck from behind.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs were first applied to automotive lighting in centre high-mount stop lamps (CHMSLs), beginning with the 1986 Chevrolet Corvette (C4).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Adoption of LEDs for other signal functions on passenger cars is gradually increasing with demand for the technology and related styling updates.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The first car registered to drive on the road with full LED rear lights was Land Rover's LCV 2/3 concept car in the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] At the time, the only light function that was difficult to reproduce was the reverse light, as white LEDs did not yet exist.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The reverse function was only achievable with the introduction of blue LEDs; by mixing red, green and blue LEDs in a defined distributed pattern behind a lens, white light was produced that conformed to the legal requirements of a reverse light.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The Maserati 3200GT, introduced in 1999, was the first production car to use full LED taillights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] In North America, the 2000 Cadillac Deville was the first passenger car with LED taillights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2002 Kia Opirus was an early adopter of LED front turn signals.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2007 Audi R8 used two strips of optically focused high-intensity LEDs for its daytime running lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Optional on the R8 outside North America were the world's first LED headlights, made by AL-Automotive Lighting.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The low and high beams, along with the position (parking) light and front turn signal, all use LEDs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The Lexus LS 600h (XF40) features LED low beam, position and side marker lights in North America, and the 2009 Cadillac Escalade Platinum used LEDs for the low and high beams, as well as for the position and side marker lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W222) used entirely LED lights, even in the most basic trim level.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lights are used for flashing beacon lights on vehicles such as maintenance trucks.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Previously, traditional light sources required the engine to continue running to ensure that the battery would not become depleted if the lights were to be used for more than a few hours.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] The energy-efficient nature of LEDs allows them to continue flashing with the engine off.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lighting systems are sensitive to heat.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Due to the negative influences of heat on the stability of photometric performance and the light transmitting components, the importance of thermal design, stability tests, usage of low-UV-type LED modules and UV-resistance tests of internal materials has increased dramatically.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] For this reason, LED signal lights must remain compliant with the intensity requirements for the functions they produce after one minute and after thirty minutes of continuous operation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] In addition, UN Regulation 112 contains a set of tests for LED modules, including colour rendering, UV radiation, and temperature stability tests.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] According to UN Regulations 112 and 123, mechanical, electromechanical or other devices for headlights must withstand endurance tests and function failure tests.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] High-intensity discharge, or HID lights, sometimes referred to as "xenon lights", are modified metal halide lights employing xenon fill gas.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Traditional HID lights, such as those used for general lighting, have a long warm-up time.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Headlights must provide light very shortly after they are turned on, and the xenon gas serves to reduce warm-up time.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon light tubes were introduced into series production for the centre high-mount stop light on the 1995 Ford Explorer.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Notable later uses included the 1998 Lincoln Mark VIII with a neon tube spanning the width of the trunk decklid, and the BMW Z8, which made extensive use of neon.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon lights offer the same nearly instant rise time as LEDs, but require a high-voltage ballast.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] In December 2023, Mercedes-Benz received approval in California and Nevada, the only states where it is legal to operate their self-driving vehicles, for turquoise lights in accordance with SAE standard J3134, to indicate to outside observers that the car's self-driving system is engaged.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Mercedes is the first car manufacturer to equip their self-driving vehicles with such lights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] In distributive light systems, the light from a single source is sent via optical fibres or light guides to wherever it is needed in the automobile.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Light guides are commonly used to distributively light dashboard displays, and premium vehicles are beginning to use distributive systems for lighting such items as door locks, window controls, and cup holders.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/automotive-lighting-p03] Distributive exterior lighting has also been explored, with high-intensity central light sources.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Governments and private organizations have developed **car classification** schemes that are used for various purposes including regulation, description, and categorization of cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The International Standard ISO 3833-1977 *Road vehicles – Types – Terms and definitions* also defines terms for classifying cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The following table summarises the commonly used terms of market segments and legal classifications.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Microcars and their Japanese equivalent— kei cars— are the smallest category of automobile.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Microcars straddle the boundary between car and motorbike, and are often covered by separate regulations from normal cars, resulting in relaxed requirements for registration and licensing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Engine size is often 700 cc (43 cu in) or less, and microcars have three or four wheels.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Microcars are most popular in Europe, where they originated following World War II.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The predecessors to micro cars are voiturettes and cycle cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Kei cars have been used in Japan since 1949.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The smallest category of vehicles that are registered as normal cars is called A-segment in Europe, or "city car" in Europe and the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency defines this category as "minicompact." However, this term is not widely used.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The equivalents of A-segment cars have been produced since the early 1920s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, the category increased in popularity in the late 1950s when the original Fiat 500 and BMC Mini were released.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The next larger category of small cars is called B-segment in Europe, supermini in the United Kingdom and subcompact in the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The size of a subcompact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of between 85–99 cubic feet (2,410–2,800 L).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Since the EPA's smaller minicompact category is not as commonly used by the general public, A-segment cars are sometimes called subcompacts in the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In Europe and Great Britain, the B-segment and supermini categories do not have any formal definitions based on size.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Early supermini cars in Great Britain include the 1977 Ford Fiesta and Vauxhall Chevette.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In the United States, the first locally-built subcompact cars were the 1970 AMC Gremlin, Chevrolet Vega, and Ford Pinto.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The largest category of small cars is called *C-segment* or *small family car* in Europe, and *compact car* in the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The size of a compact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of 100–109 cu ft (2.8–3.1 m3).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In Europe, the third-largest category for passenger cars is called *D-segment* or *large family car*.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In the United States, the equivalent term is *mid-size* or *intermediate* cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) defines a mid-size car as having a combined passenger and cargo volume of 110–119 cu ft (3.1–3.4 m3).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In Europe, the second-largest category for passenger cars is E-segment / executive car, which are usually luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In other countries, the equivalent terms are *full-size car* or *large car*, which are also used for relatively affordable large cars that are not considered luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Minivan is an American car classification for vehicles that are designed to transport passengers in the rear seating rows, and have reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The equivalent terms in British English are multi-purpose vehicle (MPV), people carrier, and people mover.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Minivans are often of the "one-box" or "two-box" body configuration, high roofs, flat floors, sliding doors for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Mini MPV is the smallest size of MPVs and the vehicles are often built on the platforms of B-segment hatchback models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The compact MPV size class includes vehicles between the mini MPV and large MPV (minivan) sizes.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Compact MPVs remain predominantly a European phenomenon, although they are also built and sold in many Latin American and Asian markets.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The largest size of minivans is also referred to as "large MPV" and became popular following the introduction of the 1984 Renault Espace and Dodge Caravan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Since the 1990s, the smaller compact MPV and mini MPV sizes of minivans have also become popular.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] If the term "minivan" is used without specifying a size, it usually refers to a large MPV.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The premium compact class (also called subcompact executive) is the smallest category of luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] It became popular in the mid-2000s, when European manufacturers — such as Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz — introduced new entry-level models that were smaller and cheaper than their compact executive models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A compact executive car or a compact luxury car is a premium car larger than a *premium compact* and smaller than an *executive car*.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Compact executive cars are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In North American terms, close equivalents are "luxury compact" and "entry-level luxury car", although the latter is also used for the smaller *premium compact cars*.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] An executive car is a premium car larger than a *compact executive* and smaller than a *full-size luxury* car.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Executive cars are classified as E-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In the United States and several other countries, the equivalent categories are full-size car (not to be confused with the European category of "full-size luxury car") or *mid-size luxury* car.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The largest size of a luxury car is known as a *luxury saloon* in the United Kingdom and a *full-size luxury car* in the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] These cars are classified as F-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Vehicles in this category are often the flagship models of luxury car brands.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Cars that prioritize handling or straight-line acceleration are called sports cars or performance cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However the term "sports car" is also sometimes used specifically for lightweight two-seat cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Sports/performance cars can either be built on unique platforms or upgraded versions of regular cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The definitions for these categories are often blurred and a car may be a member of multiple categories.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Sports cars are designed to emphasize handling, performance, or the thrill of driving.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Sports cars originated in Europe in the early 1900s, with one of the first recorded usages of the term "sports car" being in *The Times* newspaper in the United Kingdom in 1919.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Sports cars started to become popular during the 1920s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The term was originally used for two-seat roadsters (cars without fixed roofs).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, since the 1970s the term has also been used for cars with fixed roofs (which were previously considered grand tourers).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A *sports sedan* — also known as "sports saloon" — is a subjective term for a sedan/saloon car that is designed to have sporting performance or handling characteristics.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A supercar – also called an exotic car – is a loosely defined description of certain high-performance sportscars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Since the 1990s or 2000s, the term "hypercar" has come into use for the highest-performing supercars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Passenger vehicles with off-road capability or styling features are often categorized as either off-road vehicles, sports utility vehicles, or crossover SUVs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] There are no commonly agreed boundaries between these categories, and usage of the terms varies between countries.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The earliest type of passenger vehicle is called an "off-roader", "four-by-four" or "four-wheel drive".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Off-road vehicles are usually more focused on off-road capability than SUVs and crossover SUVs (often compromising their on-road ride quality or handling).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Common features of off-road vehicles are four-wheel drive, high ground clearance, a body-on-frame (separate chassis) construction and low-range gearing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A sports utility vehicle (SUV) combines elements of road-going passenger vehicles with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] There is no common definition of an SUV, and usage varies between countries.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Some definitions claim that an SUV must be built on a light-truck chassis.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, a broader definition considers any vehicle with off-road design features as an SUV.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In some countries — such as the United States — SUVs have been classified as "light trucks", resulting in more lenient regulations compared to passenger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The predecessors to SUVs date back to military and low-volume models from the late 1930s, and the four-wheel drive station wagons / carryalls that began to be introduced in 1949.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The 1984 Jeep Cherokee (XJ) is considered to be the first SUV in the modern style.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Most SUVs produced today use unibody construction (as per passenger cars).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, in the past, many SUVs used body-on-frame construction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A crossover SUV— also called a crossover or CUV— is a type of sports utility vehicle (SUV) that uses a unibody construction.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car, as a result, they typically have better comfort and fuel economy, but less off-road capability (many crossovers are sold without all-wheel drive) than truck-based SUVs, though more so than passenger four wheels.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] There are various inconsistencies about whether vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs, therefore the term SUV is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and SUVs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] These classifications can be based on body style (e.g. sedan, coupe or hatchback), number of doors or seating capacity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Government departments often create classification systems for taxation or regulating vehicle usage (e.g. vehicles that require a specific license or are restricted to certain roads).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Some jurisdictions may determine vehicle tax based upon environmental principles, such as the user pays principle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In Australia, the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries publishes its classifications.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A similar set of classes is used by the Canadian EPA.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The classification of a three-box vehicle (sedan) is determined by its length, while the classification of a two-box car (hatchback and SUV) or MPV is determined by its wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In the United Kingdom, a vehicle is taxed according to the vehicle's construction, engine, weight, type of fuel, and emissions, as well as the purpose for which it is used.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] In the United States, since 2010 the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has used a formula it developed that takes into account a combination of both vehicle footprint (length times width) and weight.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) separates vehicles into classes by the curb weight of the vehicle with standard equipment including the maximum capacity of fuel, oil, coolant, and air conditioning, if so equipped.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The United States Federal Highway Administration has developed a classification system used for automatically calculating road use tolls.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] There are two broad categories depending on whether the vehicle carries passengers or commodities.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Vehicles that carry commodities are further subdivided by the number of axles and number of units, including both power and trailer units.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) has developed a classification system used to compare fuel economy among similar vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Passenger vehicles are classified based on a vehicle's total interior passenger and cargo volumes.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Trucks are classified based on their gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Heavy-duty vehicles are not included in the EPA scheme.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Certain cities in the United States in the 1920s chose to exempt electric-powered vehicles because officials believed those vehicles did not cause "substantial wear upon the pavements".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in North America.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Cars from these segments may also be sold in other countries.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to North America.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Muscle car is an American term for high-performance cars, usually rear-wheel drive and fitted with a large and powerful V8 engine.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The term originated for the 1960s and early 1970s special editions of mass-production cars which were designed for drag racing.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Pony car is an American class of automobile launched and inspired by the Ford Mustang in 1964.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] It broke all post-World War II automobile sales records, "creating the 'pony car' craze soon adopted by competitors." The term describes an affordable, compact, highly styled car with a sporty or performance-oriented image.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A personal luxury car is a North American market segment for premium coupé or convertible produced from 1952–2007.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] These two-door cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Not prioritizing maximum interior space, interior volumes are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification, and exterior dimensions can exceed F-segment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A sporting version of an affordable compact car or a subcompact car.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] There is no precise definition and the description is applied for marketing purposes to a wide variety of models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Cars began to be marketed as sport compacts in the mid-1980s when it was used for option packages on American-built coupes.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Since then, it has also been used for standalone sports car models and cars imported from Europe and Asia.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, sport compacts are not restricted to just hatchback body styles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in Europe.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to Europe.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] A grand tourer (GT) is a car that is designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, due to a combination of performance and luxury attributes.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The most common format is a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive two-door coupé with either a two-seat or a 2+2 arrangement.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] The term derives from the Italian language phrase *gran turismo* which became popular in the English language from the 1950s, evolving from fast touring cars and streamlined closed sports cars during the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Hot hatch (shortened from hot hatchback) is a high-performance version of a mass-produced hatchback car.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, factory high-performance versions of hatchbacks have been produced since the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Front-mounted petrol engines, together with front-wheel drive, are the most common powertrain layout.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] However, all-wheel drive has become more commonly used since around 2010.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/car-classification] Most hot hatches are manufactured in Europe or Asia.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The brand has been historically popular.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] However starting in the late 2010s, the brand has been overshadowed by other brands owned by Stellantis.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] As of model year 2026, the company's production vehicle lineup solely consists of the Pacifica and Voyager minivans, although there are currently plans by Stellantis to revive the brand, as seen with the Chrysler Airflow concept, due to its heritage and continued popularity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The first Chrysler cars were introduced on January 5, 1924, at the New York Automobile Show – one year before Chrysler Corporation itself was created.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] These cars, launched by Maxwell Motors, had a new high-compression six-cylinder, a seven-bearing crankshaft, carburetor air cleaner, replaceable oil filter, and four-wheel hydraulic brakes.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Features like this had never been offered in a medium-priced car before, and the 32,000 first-year record sales proved the popularity of this model.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1926, Chrysler introduced the Chrysler 70, named for its ability to hit 70 mph.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1927, Chrysler had four models: the Chrysler 50, 60, 70, and Imperial 80.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler was in fourth place in sales, with 192,082 units delivered.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1928, Chrysler invested $23 million to expand its plants.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1930, Chrysler began wiring the Chrysler Model 70 and 77 for radios.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler also became the first car to offer the downdraft carburetor on its models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] With the new carburetor, Chrysler also received a new cam-driven fuel pump.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For the 1931 model, Chrysler received new radiator grilles, a new Chrysler Spitfire engine, and automatic spark control.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The 1932 Chryslers introduced the Floating Power rubber engine mounts, which eliminated further vibrations from the chassis.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A vacuum-controlled automatic clutch, Oilite bearings, and the first universal joints with roller bearings were also added.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1933, Chrysler models received a host of new improvements, including a new three-speed manual transmission that used helical gears – for silent use.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler engines received new alloy valve seats for better reliability, along with new spring shackles, which improved lubrication.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1934, the Chrysler 6 introduced an independent front coil spring suspension and received vent windows that rolled down with the side glass.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler also introduced its revolutionary Chrysler Airflow, which included a welded Unibody, a wind-tunnel-designed aerodynamic body for a better power-to-power ratio and better handling.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1935, Chrysler introduced the Plymouth-based Chrysler Airstream Six, which gave customers an economical modern alternative to the radically styled Airflows.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Airflow received an updated front hood and grille in 1935.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For 1936, the Chrysler Airflow received an enlarged luggage compartment, a new roof, and a new adjustable front seat.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Airstream Six and Eight of the previous year were renamed the Chrysler Six and Deluxe Eight.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Automatic overdrive was optional for both cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For 1937, the Airflow cars were mostly discontinued, besides the C-17 Airflow, which received a final facelift.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Only 4600 C-17 Airflows were built in 1937.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Chrysler Six and Chrysler Eight were respectively renamed the Royal and Imperial and gained isolated rubber body mounts to remove road vibrations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1938, the Chrysler Royal received the new 95 HP Gold Seal Inline 6.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1939, Chrysler unveiled *Superfinish* a process in which all major chassis components subject to wear were finished to a mirror-like surface.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Other features new to Chrysler were push-button door locks, and rotary-type door latches.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1940, Chrysler introduced sealed beam headlights on its cars, which in turn improved night visibility by 50%.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Mid-year, in 1940, Chrysler introduced the Highlander as a special edition featuring popular features and a Scottish plaid interior.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The luxury sport model, called the Saratoga, was also added to the New Yorker range as the Imperial became the exclusive limousine model.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1941, Chrysler introduced the Fluid Drive semi-automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] 1942 Chryslers were redesigned with a wrap-a-round chrome grille and concealed running boards for this abbreviated model year; civilian production stopped by February 1942.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1946, Chrysler redesigned the 1942 cars and reintroduced the Town & Country.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1949, Chrysler came out with the first all-new redesign in almost a decade.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1949, Chrysler moved the ignition to key only instead of having a key and push-button.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] They also reintroduced the nine-passenger station wagon body style to the line.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For 1950, Chrysler updated the overly conservative 1949 models by lowering cars slightly, updating the grille to appear more simple, replacing the chrome fin tail lamps with flush units, and removing the third brake light from the trunk lid.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Also in 1950, Chrysler introduced disc brakes on the Imperial, the new Chrysler Newport hardtop, power windows, and the padded safety dash.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler introduced their first overhead-valve, high-compression V8 engine in 1951; displacing 331 cubic inches, it was rated at 180 bhp, 20 more horsepower than the new-for-1949 Cadillac V8.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was unique as the only American V8 engine designed with hemispherical combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] After successfully winning Mexican Road Races, the engine was upgraded to 250 bhp by 1955.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Although Chrysler did not build a small sporty car (such as the Chevrolet Corvette and the Ford Thunderbird), they decided to build a unique sporting car based on the New Yorker hardtop coupe that featured a 300-bhp "Hemi" V8.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] To add to the car's uniqueness, the car was given a grille from the Imperial and side trim from the less-adorned Windsor.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A PowerFlite 2-speed automatic transmission was the only available gearbox.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was marketed as the Chrysler 300, emphasizing the engine's horsepower, continuing a luxury sport approach introduced earlier with the Chrysler Saratoga.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1955, the flagship Imperial was spun off into its own line of luxury cars, slotted above Chrysler, Imperial would remain a separate brand through 1975, and would be reintroduced in 1980, offering a single model through 1983.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Imperial returned as the flagship Chrysler for model years 1990-1993.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A 1955 restyle by newly hired Virgil Exner saw a dramatic rise in Chrysler sales, which rose even more in 1957 when the entire line was dramatically restyled a second time with a sloping front end and high-flying tailfins at the rear.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Although well received at first, it soon became apparent that quality control was compromised to get the new cars to market on an accelerated schedule.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1957, all Chrysler products were installed with Torsion-Aire front suspension, which was a Torsion bar suspension only for the front wheels that followed two years after Packard installed Torsion-Level suspension on both the front and rear wheels.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Sales of all Chrysler models plummeted in 1958 and 1959 despite improvements in quality.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Throughout the mid-and late-1950s, Chryslers were available in top-line New Yorker, mid-line Saratoga, and base Windsor series.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Exner's designs for the Chrysler brand in the early 1960s were overblown versions of the late 1950s, which were unhelpful in sales.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Exner left his post by 1962, leaving Elwood Engel, a recent transfer from Ford Motor Co, in charge of Chrysler styling.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Although early 1960s Chrysler cars reflected Virgil Exner's exaggerated styling, Elwood Engel's influence was evident as early as 1963, when a restyled, trimmer, boxier Chrysler was introduced.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Desoto lines, along with the Windsor and Saratoga series, were replaced with the Newport, while New Yorker continued as the luxury model, while Imperial continued to be the top-of-the-line brand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Chrysler 300, officially part of the New Yorker product line, continued in production as a high-performance coupe through 1965, adding a different letter of the alphabet for each year of production, starting with the 300-B of 1956, through the 300-L of 1965.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] 1962 saw a "non-letter" 300, which was lower in price but was equipped with downgraded standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The 1965 Chryslers were again dramatically restyled, with a thoroughly modern unit body and larger engines up to 413 cubic inches.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] They were squared off and slab-sided, with optional glass-covered headlamps that retracted when the headlights were turned on and a swept-back roofline for 2-door hardtop models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1963, Bob Hope was a spokesperson of *The Chrysler Theatre*, an anthology series sponsored by the brand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The same year the Chrysler Turbine Car was introduced.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was an experimental two-door hardtop coupe powered by a turbine engine and manufactured from 1963 to 1964.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Italian design studio Carrozzeria Ghia constructed the bodywork, and Chrysler completed the final assembly in Detroit.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A total of 55 Turbine Cars were manufactured.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Cordoba was introduced by Chrysler for the 1975 model year as an upscale personal luxury car that replaced the 300, competing with the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Buick Regal, and Mercury Cougar.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Cordoba was originally intended to be a Plymouth—the names Mirada, Premier, Sebring, and Grand Era were associated with the project; all except Grand Era would be used on later Chrysler, Dodge, and Eagle vehicles, though only the Dodge Mirada would be related to the Cordoba.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] However, losses from the newly introduced full-size C-body models due to the 1973 oil crisis, along with the investment in the Turbine Car that did not produce a product to sell, encouraged Chrysler executives to seek higher profits by marketing the model under the more upscale Chrysler brand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The car was a success, with over 150,000 examples sold in 1975, a sales year that was otherwise dismal for the company.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For the 1976 model year, sales increased slightly to 165,000.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The mildly revised 1977 version also sold well, with just under 140,000 cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The success of using the Chrysler nameplate strategy is contrasted to sales of its similar and somewhat cheaper corporate cousin, the Dodge Charger SE.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Interiors were more luxurious than the Dodge Charger SE and much more than the top-line standard intermediates (Plymouth Fury, Dodge Coronet) with a velour cloth notchback bench seat and folding armrest standard.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Optionally available were bucket seats upholstered in Corinthian leather with a center armrest and cushion or, at extra cost, a center console with floor shifter and storage compartment.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1977, Chrysler brought out a new mid-size line of cars called LeBaron (a name previously used for an Imperial model), which included a coupe, sedan, and station wagon.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1982, the LeBaron moved to the front-wheel drive Chrysler K platform, where it was the upscale brand's lowest-priced offering.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was initially available in just sedan and coupe versions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In early 1982, it was released in a convertible version, bringing to the market the first factory-built open-topped domestic vehicle since the 1976 Cadillac Eldorado.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A station wagon version called the **Town and Country** was added as well.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A special Town and Country convertible was also made from 1983 until 1986 in limited quantities (1,105 total), which, like the wagon, featured simulated wood paneling that made it resemble the original 1940s Town and Country.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] This model was part of the well-equipped Mark Cross option package for the latter years.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1982, the R-body line was discontinued, and the New Yorker nameplate transferred to the smaller M-body line.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Up to this point, the Chrysler M-body entry had been sold as LeBaron, but that name was moved to a new K-car-based FWD line (refer to the Chrysler LeBaron article for information on the 1977–81 M-bodies).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Following the nameplate swap, the M-body line was consolidated and simplified.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] 360 V8 engines were gone, as were coupes and station wagons (the K-car LeBaron's coupe and wagon replaced them).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Fifth Avenue option was still available as a $1,244 option package.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was adapted from the earlier LeBaron's package, with a distinctive vinyl roof, electroluminescent opera lamps, and a rear fascia adapted from the Dodge Diplomat.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Interiors featured button-tufted, pillow-soft seats covered in either "Kimberley velvet" or "Corinthian leather," choices that would continue unchanged throughout the car's run.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In addition, the carpet was thicker than that offered in the base New Yorker, Diplomat and Gran Fury/Caravelle Salon, and the interior had more chrome trim.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The last year for Chrysler's Cordoba coupe was 1983.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] That year, Chrysler introduced a new front-wheel-drive New Yorker model based on a stretched K-Car platform.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Additionally, a less expensive, less equipped version of the new New Yorker was sold as the Chrysler E-Class in 1983 and 1984.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] More upscale stretched K-Car models were also sold as Chrysler Executive sedans and limousines.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] With the 1984 model year, the New Yorker Fifth Avenue was now simply called Fifth Avenue, setting the name that would continue for six successful years.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Fifth Avenue production was moved from Windsor, Ontario to St.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Beginning in late 1986 through the 1989 model year, they were manufactured at the American Motors plant in Kenosha, Wisconsin (purchased by Chrysler in 1987).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Fifth Avenue also far outsold its Dodge Diplomat and Plymouth Gran Fury siblings, with a much greater proportion of sales going to private customers despite its higher price tag.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Production peaked at 118,000 cars for 1986, and the Fifth Avenue stood out in a by-now K-car-dominated lineup as Chrysler's lone concession to traditional RWD American sedans.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler introduced a new mid-size four-door hatchback model in 1985 under the LeBaron GTS nameplate.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was sold alongside the mid-size LeBaron sedan, coupe, convertible, and station wagon.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The LeBaron coupe and convertible were redesigned in 1987.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Unlike previous LeBarons, this new coupe and convertible had unique styling instead of being just two-door versions of the sedan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The new design featured hidden headlamps (through 1992) and full-width taillights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker was redesigned for the 1988 model year and now included a standard V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] This generation of New Yorker also saw the return of hidden headlamps, which had not been available on the New Yorker since the 1981 R-body version.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1989, Chrysler brought out the TC by Maserati luxury roadster as a more affordable alternative to Cadillac's Allante.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was a joint venture model between Chrysler and Maserati.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] 1990 saw the previous relationship between New Yorker and Fifth Avenue return, as Fifth Avenue became a model of the New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] There was some substantive difference, however, as the New Yorker Fifth Avenue used a slightly longer chassis than the standard car.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The new New Yorker Fifth Avenue's larger interior volume classified it as a full-size model this time despite having smaller exterior dimensions than the first generation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For 1990, Chrysler's new 3.3L V6 engine was the standard and only choice, teamed with the company's A-604 four-speed electronic automatic transaxle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Beginning in 1991, a larger 3.8L V6 became optional.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It delivered the same 147 horsepower as the 3.3 but had more torque.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker Fifth Avenue's famous seats, long noted for their button-tufted appearance and sofa-like comfort, continued to be offered with the customer's choice of velour or leather, with the former "Corinthian leather" replaced by that of the Mark Cross company.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Leather-equipped cars bore the Mark Cross logo on the seats and, externally, on an emblem attached to the brushed aluminum band ahead of the rear door opera windows.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The early 1990s saw a revival of the Imperial as a high-end sedan in Chrysler's lineup.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Unlike the 1955 through 1983 Imperial, this car was a model of Chrysler, not its own marque.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Based on the Y platform, it represented the top full-size model in Chrysler's lineup; below it was the similar New Yorker Fifth Avenue, and below that was the shorter wheelbase New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The reintroduction of the Imperial was two years after the Lincoln Continental was changed to a front-wheel-drive sedan with a V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Other domestic competitors in this segment included the Cadillac Sedan de Ville/Fleetwood, Oldsmobile 98, and Buick Electra/Park Avenue.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Though closely related, the Imperial differed from the New Yorker Fifth Avenue in many ways.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Imperial's nose was more wedge-shaped, while the New Yorker Fifth Avenue's had a sharper, more angular profile (the New Yorker Fifth Avenue was later restyled with a more rounded front end).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The rears of the two cars also differed.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Like the front, the New Yorker Fifth Avenue's rear came to stiffer angles, while the Imperial's rear end came to more rounded edges.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Also found on the Imperial were full-width taillights, which were similar to those of the Chrysler TC, as well as the early 1980s Imperial coupe, while the New Yorker Fifth Avenue came with smaller vertical taillights.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Initially, the 1990 Imperial was powered by the 147 hp (110 kW) 3.3L *EGA* V6 engine, which was rated at 185 lb⋅ft (251 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For 1991, the 3.3L V6 was replaced by the larger 3.8L *EGH* V6.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Although horsepower only increased to 150 hp (112 kW), with the new larger 3.8L V6 torque increased to 215 lb⋅ft (292 N⋅m) at 2750 rpm.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A four-speed automatic transmission was standard with both engines.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Also new for 1990 was a redesigned LeBaron sedan, which offered a standard V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Later models would also be available with 4-cylinder engines.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Town & Country minivan was restyled for 1991 in conjunction with the restyling of the Dodge and Plymouth minivan models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] 1991 would also be the last year for the TC by Maserati, leaving the LeBaron as the brand's sole coupe and convertible options.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The first generation of the Chrysler Concorde debuted at the 1992 North American International Auto Show in Detroit as a 1993 model.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It debuted as a single, well-equipped model with a base price of US$18,341.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Out of all the LH sedans, the first generation Concorde was most closely related to the Eagle Vision.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Concorde was given a more traditional image than the Vision.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The two shared nearly all sheet metal in common, with the main differences limited to their grilles, rear fascias, bodyside moldings, and wheel choices.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Concorde featured a modern take on Chrysler's signature waterfall grille.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was split into six sections divided by body-colored strips with the Chrysler Pentastar logo on the center strip.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Concorde's rear fascia was highlighted by a full-width and full-height lightbar between the taillights, giving the appearance that the taillights stretched across the entire trunk.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In keeping with its upscale position, Concorde's body side moldings incorporated bright chrome (later golden-colored) work not found on its Dodge or Eagle siblings.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] On Concordes with gray lower body paint color, the gray came up to the chrome beltline; on Visions, the gray lower body paint area was smaller and much more subtle.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Wheel styles, which included available aluminum wheels with a Spiralcast design, were also unique to the Chrysler LH sedans (Concorde, LHS, New Yorker); Dodge and Eagle had different wheel styles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Introduced in May 1993 for the 1994 model year, the Chrysler LHS was the top-of-the-line model for the division, as well as the most expensive of the Chrysler LH platform cars.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] All the LH-series models shared a 113.0-inch (2,870 mm) wheelbase and were developed using Chrysler's new computer drafting system.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The car was differentiated from the division's New Yorker sedan by its bucket leather seats (the New Yorker had a bench seat) and standard features such as alloy wheels that were options on the New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Further differences between the Chrysler LHS and its New Yorker counterpart were a floor console and shifter, five-passenger seating, lack of chrome trim, an upgraded interior, and a sportier image.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker was dropped after the 1996 model year in favor of a six-passenger option on the LHS.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The LHS received a minor face change in 1995 when the corporate-wide Pentastar emblem was replaced with the revived Chrysler brand emblem.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Unlike the New Yorker, leather seats were standard.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker came standard with the 3.5L *EGE* which produced 214 hp (160 kW).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler gave the New Yorker a more "traditional American" luxury image and the LHS a more European performance image (as was done with the Eagle Vision).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Little separated New Yorker from LHS in appearance, with New Yorker's chrome hood trim, body-color cladding, standard chrome wheel covers, 15-inch wheels, column shifter, and front bench seat being the only noticeable differences.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] An option is provided for 16-inch wheels and a firmer suspension type ("touring suspension").
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] This option eliminated the technical differences between New Yorker and LHS.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] LHS came with almost all of New Yorker's optional features as standard equipment and featured the firmer tuned suspension to go with its more European image.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] During the 1994 model run, various changes were made to the New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] On the outside, New Yorker was switched to new accent-color body cladding, whereas LHS received body-color cladding.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] This change aligned the New Yorker with the Chrysler Concorde, which also had accent-color cladding.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Instead of standard 15-inch and optional 16-inch wheels, the 16-inch wheels became standard, and the 15-inch versions were dropped.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Likewise, the touring suspension option available on early 1994 New Yorker models was discontinued, leaving only "ride-tuned" suspension.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1995, the Chrysler Sebring was introduced as a coupe, replacing the LeBaron coupe, and the new JA platform Chrysler Cirrus replaced the outgoing LeBaron sedan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A year later, a convertible version of the Sebring went on the market and replaced the LeBaron convertible.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 1999, Chrysler introduced the new LH platform 300M sedan alongside a redesigned LHS.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The 300M was originally designed to be the next-generation Eagle Vision, but since the Eagle brand had been discontinued in 1998, it instead became a Chrysler sedan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 2000, the Voyager and Grand Voyager minivans were repositioned as Chrysler models due to the phasing out of the Plymouth brand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 2001, a sedan was added to the Sebring model line and served as a replacement for the discontinued Cirrus.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] That same year, the Chrysler brand added a retro-styled PT Cruiser as well as the Prowler roadster which had previously been a Plymouth model.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] By 2004, all Chrysler brand minivans were now sold under the Town & Country nameplate.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The 2000s also saw the Chrysler brand move into the fast-growing crossover/SUV segment with the introduction of the Chrysler Pacifica crossover in 2004 and the Chrysler Aspen SUV in 2007.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The Pacifica would be discontinued in 2008 (the nameplate would return on a new minivan model in 2017), and the Aspen would be discontinued in 2009.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Between 2004 and 2008, Chrysler offered a two-seat coupe and convertible model called Crossfire.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] This was in addition to Chrysler's five-seat Sebring coupe (through 2005) and four-seat convertible being sold at the time.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 2005, Chrysler introduced the LX platform Chrysler 300 sedan, which replaced both the 300M and Concorde.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was the brand's first rear-wheel-drive sedan since the discontinuation of the Chrysler Fifth Avenue in 1989.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] It was also the first time a Chrysler sedan was available with a V8 engine since 1989.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler Corporation began working with Italian automaker Fiat, culminating with the 2014 merger of the two companies.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The newly formed Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA) set a long-term goal of reviving the Chrysler brand as a full luxury brand to compete again with Cadillac and other luxury brands, partly by rebadging automobiles from other brands in the group.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] However, none of these plans ultimately came to fruition in the decade.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In 2011, the brand's winged emblem was modified, eliminating the historic blue ribbon center which dated from the 1930s, replacing it with a blue-backed "Chrysler" nameplate.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Also that year, the Chrysler 300 was restyled, and the Sebring was rebranded as the Chrysler 200.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In May 2014, FCA announced it would make the brand a mainstream brand with premium features.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] A redesigned Chrysler 200 was introduced for 2015 but would be discontinued in 2017 as FCA shifted focus more towards SUVs and minivans.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] For 2017, the Chrysler Pacifica nameplate returned on a new minivan, replacing the long-running Town & Country, Voyager, and Grand Voyager.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] During this time, Chrysler's quality and customer satisfaction ratings had been below average, according to Consumer Reports and J.D.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler did have a few quality successes during this period.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Strategic Vision named Chrysler an overall winner in 2015 for strong customer appeal, and with the rise in quality of all cars, the difference between high and low "problem-counting" ratings is relatively small.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In the early 2020s, Chrysler was facing an uncertain future with just two vehicle models in its lineup: the Chrysler Pacifica minivan and the Chrysler 300 sedan, which was last redesigned in 2010.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In March 2023, Stellantis CEO Carlos Tavares said the brand would be "relaunched" with new models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] One of those models is expected to be an electric crossover SUV by 2025, previewed by the Chrysler Airflow concept.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] In December 2023, the Chrysler 300 was discontinued.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Furthermore, the company says it plans to make the Chrysler brand fully electric by 2028.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] Chrysler's product lineup in North America by 2030 will include the Pacifica, Airflow, Arrow, and Arrow Cross.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-brand] The brand's current lineup consists of the Chrysler Pacifica minivan and its sister vehicle the Chrysler Voyager.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The original Chrysler Corporation was founded in 1925 by Walter Chrysler from the remains of the Maxwell Motor Company.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1998, it merged with Daimler-Benz, which renamed itself DaimlerChrysler but in 2007 sold off its Chrysler stake.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company operated as Chrysler LLC through 2009, then as Chrysler Group LLC.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2014, it was acquired by Fiat S.p.A.; it subsequently operated as a subsidiary of the new Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), then as a subsidiary of Stellantis, the company formed from the 2021 merger of FCA and PSA Group (Peugeot Société Anonyme).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] After founding the company, Walter Chrysler used General Motors (GM)'s brand diversification and hierarchy strategy that he knew of when he worked at its Buick division.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] He then acquired Fargo Trucks and the Dodge Brothers Company, and created the Plymouth and DeSoto brands in 1928.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Facing postwar declines in market share, productivity, and profitability, as GM and Ford were growing, Chrysler borrowed $250 million in 1954 from Prudential Insurance to pay for expansion and updated car designs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler expanded into Europe by taking control of French, British, and Spanish auto companies in the 1960s; but in 1978 Chrysler Europe was sold to PSA Peugeot Citroën for a nominal $1.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company struggled to adapt to changing markets, increased U.S. import competition, and safety and environmental regulation in the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] It began an engineering partnership with Mitsubishi Motors, and began selling Mitsubishi vehicles branded as Dodge and Plymouth in North America.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On the verge of bankruptcy in the late 1970s, it was saved by $1.5 billion in loan guarantees from the U.S. government.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] New CEO Lee Iacocca was credited with returning the company to profitability in the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1985, Diamond-Star Motors was created, further expanding the Chrysler-Mitsubishi relationship.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1987, Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation (AMC), which brought the profitable Jeep, as well as the newly formed Eagle, brands under the Chrysler umbrella.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1998, Chrysler merged with German automaker Daimler-Benz to form DaimlerChrysler AG; the merger proved contentious with investors.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] As a result, Chrysler was sold to Cerberus Capital Management and renamed Chrysler LLC in 2007.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Like the other Big Three automobile manufacturers, Chrysler was affected by the automotive industry crisis of 2008–2010.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company remained in business through a combination of negotiations with creditors, filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization on April 30, 2009, and participating in a bailout from the U.S. government through the Troubled Asset Relief Program.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On June 10, 2009, Chrysler emerged from the bankruptcy proceedings with the United Auto Workers pension fund, Fiat S.p.A., and the U.S. and Canadian governments as principal owners.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The bankruptcy resulted in Chrysler defaulting on over $4 billion in debts.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In May 2011, Chrysler finished repaying its obligations to the U.S. government five years early, although the cost to the American taxpayer was $1.3 billion.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Over the next few years, Fiat S.p.A. gradually acquired the other parties' shares.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In January 2014, Fiat acquired the rest of Chrysler from the United Auto Workers retiree health trust, making Chrysler Group a subsidiary of Fiat S.p.A.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In May 2014, Fiat Chrysler Automobiles was established by merging Fiat S.p.A. into the company.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler Group LLC remained a subsidiary until December 15, 2014, when it was renamed FCA US LLC, to reflect the Fiat-Chrysler merger.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] As a result of the merger between FCA and PSA, on 17 January 2021 it became a subsidiary of the Stellantis Group.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Chrysler company was founded by Walter Chrysler on June 6, 1925, when the Maxwell Motor Company (est.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] 1904) was re-organized into the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company was headquartered in the Detroit enclave of Highland Park, where it remained until completing the move to its present Auburn Hills location in 1996.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler had arrived at the ailing Maxwell-Chalmers company in the early 1920s, hired to overhaul the company's troubled operations (after a similar rescue job at the Willys-Overland car company).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In late 1923, production of the Chalmers automobile was ended.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In January 1924, Walter Chrysler launched the well-received Chrysler automobile.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Chrysler Six was designed to provide customers with an advanced, well-engineered car, at an affordable price.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Elements of this car are traceable to a prototype which had been under development at Willys during Chrysler's tenure The original 1924 Chrysler included a carburetor air filter, high compression engine, full pressure lubrication, and an oil filter, features absent from most autos at the time.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Among the innovations in its early years were the first practical mass-produced four-wheel hydraulic brakes, a system nearly completely engineered by Chrysler with patents assigned to Lockheed, and rubber engine mounts, called "Floating Power" to reduce vibration.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler also developed a wheel with a ridged rim, designed to keep a deflated tire from flying off the wheel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] This wheel was eventually adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Maxwell brand was dropped after the 1925 model year, with the new, lower-priced four-cylinder Chryslers introduced for the 1926 year being badge-engineered Maxwells.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The advanced engineering and testing that went into Chrysler Corporation cars helped to push the company to the second-place position in U.S. sales by 1936, which it held until 1949.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1928, the Chrysler Corporation began dividing its vehicle offerings by price class and function.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Plymouth brand was introduced at the low-priced end of the market (created essentially by once again reworking and rebadging the Chrysler Series 50 four-cylinder model).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] At the same time, the DeSoto brand was introduced in the medium-price field.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Also in 1928, Chrysler bought the Dodge Brothers automobile and truck company and continued the successful Dodge line of automobiles and Fargo range of trucks.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] By the mid-1930s, the DeSoto and Dodge divisions would trade places in the corporate hierarchy.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Imperial name had been used since 1926 but was never a separate make, just the top-of-the-line Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] However, in 1955, the company decided to offer it as its own make/brand and division to better compete with its rivals, Lincoln and Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] This addition changed the company's traditional four-make lineup to five (in order of price from bottom to top): Plymouth, Dodge, DeSoto, Chrysler, and the now-separate Imperial.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On April 28, 1955, Chrysler and Philco announced the development and production of the World's First All-Transistor car radio.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The all-transistor car radio, Mopar model 914HR, developed and produced by Chrysler and Philco, was a $150 option on the 1956 Imperial automobile models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Philco began manufacturing this radio in the fall of 1955 at its Sandusky Ohio plant.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On September 28, 1957, Chrysler announced the first production electronic fuel injection (EFI), as an option on some of its new 1958 car models (Chrysler 300D, Dodge D500, DeSoto Adventurer, Plymouth Fury).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The first attempt to use this system was by American Motors on the 1957 Rambler Rebel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Bendix Corporation's Electrojector used a transistor "computer brain" modulator box, but teething problems on pre-production cars meant very few cars were made.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The EFI system in the Rambler ran fine in warm weather, but suffered hard starting in cooler temperatures and AMC decided not to use this EFI system on its 1957 Rambler Rebel production cars that were sold to the public.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler also used the Bendix "Electrojector" fuel injection system and only around 35 vehicles were built with this option, on its 1958 production-built car models.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Owners of EFI Chryslers were so dissatisfied that all but one were retrofitted with carburetors (while that one has been completely restored, with original EFI electronic problems resolved).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Valiant was also introduced for the 1960 model year as a distinct brand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In the U.S. market, Valiant was made a model in the Plymouth line for 1961 and the DeSoto make was discontinued in 1961.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] With those exceptions per applicable year and market, Chrysler's range from lowest to highest price from the 1940s through the 1970s was Valiant, Plymouth, Dodge, DeSoto, Chrysler, and Imperial.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1954, Chrysler was the exclusive provider of its Hemi V8 engine in the Facel Vega, a French coachbuilder that offered its own line of hand-built luxury performance cars, coupled with the PowerFlite and TorqueFlite automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Facel Vega Excellence was a four-door hardtop with rear-hinged coach doors that listed for US$12,800 ($142,837 in 2025 dollars ).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1960 Facel Vega introduced the smaller Facellia sports car to capitalize on its sales success with Chrysler supplied engines.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] At the time, Chrysler didn't produce a four-cylinder engine, and the company had to find alternatives before production began.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] From 1963 through 1969, Chrysler increased its existing stakes to take complete control of the French Simca, British Rootes, and Spanish Barreiros companies, merging them into Chrysler Europe in 1967.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In the 1970s, an engineering partnership was established with Mitsubishi Motors, and Chrysler began selling Mitsubishi vehicles branded as Dodge and Plymouth in North America.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler struggled to adapt to the changing environment of the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] When consumer tastes shifted to smaller cars in the early 1970s, particularly after the 1973 oil crisis, Chrysler could not meet the demand, although its compact models on the "A" body platform, the Dodge Dart and Plymouth Valiant, had proven economy and reliability and sold very well.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Additional burdens came from increased US import competition, and tougher government regulation of car safety, fuel economy, and emissions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] As the smallest of the Big 3 US automakers, Chrysler lacked the financial resources to meet all of these challenges.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] 1975 would be the last year for Imperial, except for an ill-fated attempt at revival in 1981-1983, for its low sales no longer justified it as a separate brand when it didn't offer much over a high-end Chrysler New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1976, with the demise of the reliable Dart/Valiant, quality control declined.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Their replacements, the Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volare, were comfortable and had good roadability, but owners soon experienced major reliability problems which crept into other models as well.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Engines failed and/or did not run well, and premature rust plagued bodies.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1978, Lee Iacocca was brought in to turn the company around, and in 1979 Iacocca sought US government help.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Congress later passed the *Loan Guarantee Act* providing $1.5 billion in loan guarantees.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Also in 1978, Iacocca offloaded the ailing European operation to PSA Peugeot Citroën for a nominal $1, taking with it the group's substantial losses and debts which had been dragging the rest of the business down.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler returned to profitability in 1980, repaying the loans with interest in 1983.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Omni/Horizon were first offered with four-cylinder engines provided by Chrysler Europe brand Simca, then Volkswagen, until the all-new Chrysler engineered Chrysler K engine arrived.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler had not manufactured a four-cylinder engine since 1933 when the Chrysler flathead four-cylinder was canceled.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In November 1983, the Dodge Caravan/Plymouth Voyager was introduced, built on a modified K platform, establishing the minivan as a major category, and initiating Chrysler's return to stability.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1985, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors Corporation to produce Chrysler M platform rear-drive, as well as Dodge Omnis front wheel drive cars, in AMC's Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1987, Chrysler acquired the 47% ownership of AMC that was held by Renault.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The remaining outstanding shares of AMC were bought on the NYSE by August 5, 1987, making the deal valued somewhere between US$1.7 billion and US$2 billion, depending on how costs were counted.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted the Jeep brand, particularly the Jeep Grand Cherokee (ZJ) that was under development, the new world-class manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, and AMC's engineering and management talent that became critical for Chrysler's future success.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler established the Jeep/Eagle division as a "specialty" arm to market products distinctly different from the K-car-based products with the Eagle cars targeting import buyers.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Former AMC dealers sold Jeep vehicles and various new Eagle models, as well as Chrysler products, strengthening the automaker's retail distribution system.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Eurostar, a joint venture between Chrysler and Steyr-Daimler-Puch, began producing the Chrysler Voyager in Austria for European markets in 1992.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1998, Chrysler and its subsidiaries entered into a partnership dubbed a "merger of equals" with German-based Daimler-Benz AG, creating the combined entity DaimlerChrysler AG.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] To the surprise of many stockholders, Daimler acquired Chrysler in a stock swap before Chrysler CEO Bob Eaton retired.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Under DaimlerChrysler, the company was named DaimlerChrysler Motors Company LLC, with its U.S. operations generally called "DCX".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Eagle brand was retired soon after Chrysler's merger with Daimler-Benz in 1998 Jeep became a stand-alone division, and efforts were made to merge the Chrysler and Jeep brands as one sales unit.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2001, the Plymouth brand was also discontinued.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Eurostar also built the Chrysler PT Cruiser in 2001 and 2002.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Austrian venture was sold to Magna International in 2002 and became Magna Steyr.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Voyager continued in production until 2007, whereas the Chrysler 300C, Jeep Grand Cherokee, and Jeep Commander were also built at the plant from 2005 until 2010.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On May 14, 2007, DaimlerChrysler announced the sale of 80.1% of Chrysler Group to American private equity firm Cerberus Capital Management, L.P., thereafter known as Chrysler LLC, although Daimler (renamed as Daimler AG) continued to hold a 19.9% stake.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The economic collapse during the 2008 financial crisis pushed the company to the brink.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On April 30, 2009, the automaker filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection to be able to operate as a going concern, while renegotiating its debt structure and other obligations, which resulted in the corporation defaulting on over $4 billion in secured debts.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The U.S. government described the company's action as a "prepackaged surgical bankruptcy".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On June 10, 2009, substantially all of Chrysler's assets were sold to "New Chrysler", organized as Chrysler Group LLC.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The federal government provided support for the deal with US$8 billion in financing at nearly 21%.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Under CEO Sergio Marchionne, "World Class Manufacturing" or WCM, a system of thorough manufacturing quality, was introduced and several products were re-launched with quality and luxury.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Ram, Jeep, Dodge, SRT, and Chrysler divisions were separated to focus on their own identity and brand, and 11 major model refreshes occurred in 21 months.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The PT Cruiser, Nitro, Liberty and Caliber models (created during DCX) were discontinued.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On May 24, 2011, Chrysler repaid its $7.6 billion loans to the United States and Canadian governments.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The US Treasury, through the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP), invested $12.5 billion in Chrysler and recovered $11.2 billion when the company shares were sold in May 2011, resulting in a $1.3 billion loss.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On July 21, 2011, Fiat bought the Chrysler shares held by the US Treasury.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The purchase made Chrysler foreign-owned again, this time as the luxury division.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Chrysler 300 was badged Lancia Thema in some European markets (with additional engine options), giving Lancia a much-needed replacement for its flagship.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On January 21, 2014, Fiat bought the remaining shares of Chrysler owned by the VEBA worth $3.65 billion.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Several days later, the intended reorganization of Fiat and Chrysler under a new holding company, Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), together with a new logo were announced.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The most challenging launch for this new company came immediately in January 2014 with a completely redesigned Chrysler 200.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The vehicle's creation is from the completely integrated company, FCA, executing from a global compact-wide platform.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On December 16, 2014, Chrysler Group LLC announced a name change to FCA US LLC.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On January 12, 2017, FCA shares traded at the New York Stock Exchange lost value after the EPA accused FCA US of using emissions cheating software to evade diesel-emissions tests, however the company countered the accusations, and the chairman and CEO Sergio Marchionne sternly rejected them.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The following day, shares rose as investors played down the effect of the accusations.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Analysts gave estimates of potential fines from several hundred million dollars to $4 billion, although the likelihood of a hefty fine was low.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Senior United States Senator Bill Nelson urged the FTC to look into possible deceptive marketing of the company's diesel-powered SUVs.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Shares dropped 2.2% after the announcement.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] FCA US would in 2022, plead guilty to a criminal charge of conspiring to defraud the US, to wire fraud, and to violate the Clean Air Act.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On July 21, 2018, Sergio Marchionne stepped down as chairman and CEO for health reasons, and was replaced by John Elkann and Michael Manley, respectively.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] It was again fined for the 2017 model year for not meeting the minimum domestic passenger car standard.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company was also to pay affected consumers up to $280 million and offer extended warranties on such vehicles worth $105 million.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The total value of the settlement was about $800 million, though FCA did not admit liability, and it did not resolve an ongoing criminal investigation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On December 21, 2020, the European Commission approved the merger between FCA and PSA Group with minimal conditions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Shareholders approved the deal on January 4, 2021, and the merger was finalized on January 16, 2021, with FCA US now part of a new entity: Stellantis.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Stellantis shares began trading under the symbol “STLA” on the Milan Stock Exchange and Euronext Paris on January 18, followed by the New York Stock Exchange on January 19, and on the New York Stock Exchange on 19 January.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] For accounting purposes, PSA was designated the acquirer, and financial statements reflect PSA's historical performance.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Under Carlos Tavares' leadership, Stellantis faced growing criticism over its cost-cutting strategy, declining sales, and strained relations with key stakeholders.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Tavares implemented aggressive restructuring measures, including job cuts and strict control over product development, which some analysts blamed for delays in launching new models and weakening brand performance, particularly at Stellantis North America.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] U.S. dealers expressed concern about rising inventories and brand mismanagement, while the United Auto Workers criticized the company over job cuts and halted investment plans.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2024, Stellantis reported a 70% drop in net profit, with global shipments and U.S. market share declining significantly.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Amid internal friction with the board and worsening financial performance, Tavares resigned in December 2024, two years before his contract was set to expire.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On May 28, 2025, the board of Stellantis unanimously appointed Antonio Filosa, a longtime executive who had led Stellantis operations in North and South America, as CEO starting June 23.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Filosa is expected to place renewed emphasis on the North American market.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] However, the majority of its management team remains based in Europe.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Following the appointment of Filosa, formerly COO of Stellantis North America, Stellantis announced on June 10, 2025, that he would be based in Auburn Hills, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] His predecessor, Carlos Tavares, former CEO of PSA, was based in Europe and regularly worked remotely from his Portuguese property.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] He was considered by some to have insufficient presence in the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On October 14, 2025, Stellantis announced an investment of $13 billion to strengthen its growth in the United States over the next four years.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company claims this is its largest investment in its century-long history in the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Belvidere, Illinois, plant will reopen for production of two new Jeep Cherokee and Jeep Compass vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company also said it will create more than 5,000 manufacturing jobs in four Midwestern U.S. states.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] On May 20, 2026, Stellantis and British luxury carmaker Jaguar Land Rover signed a memorandum of understanding to "explore synergies in areas such as product and technology development" within the United States.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Stellantis is the smallest of the "Big Three", which also includes Ford and GM.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2020, it sold just over 1.8 million vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler was the world's 11th largest vehicle manufacturer as ranked by OICA in 2012.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Total Chrysler vehicle production was about 2.37 million that year.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The company has since become a wholly owned subsidiary and no longer reports global sales.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2007, Chrysler began to offer vehicle lifetime powertrain warranty for the first registered owner or retail lessee.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The deal covered owner or lessee in U.S., Puerto Rico, and the Virgin Islands, for 2009 model year vehicles, and 2006, 2007, and 2008 model year vehicles purchased on or after July 26, 2007.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Covered vehicles excluded SRT models, Diesel vehicles, Sprinter models, Ram Chassis Cab, Hybrid System components (including transmission), and certain fleet vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] After Chrysler's restructuring, the warranty program was replaced by five-year/100,000 mile transferable warranty for 2010 or later vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2008, as a response to customer feedback citing the prospect of rising gas prices as a top concern, Chrysler launched the "Let's Refuel America" incentive campaign, which guaranteed new-car buyers a gasoline price of $2.99 for three years.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] With the U.S. purchase of eligible Chrysler, Jeep, and Dodge vehicles, customers could enroll in the program and receive a gas card that immediately lowers their gas price to $2.99 a gallon, and keeps it there for the three years.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler plans for Lancia to codevelop products, with some vehicles being shared.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Olivier Francois, Lancia's CEO, was appointed to the Chrysler division in October 2009.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Francois plans to reestablish the Chrysler brand as an upscale brand.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In October 2009, Dodge's car and truck lines were separated, with the name "Dodge" being used for cars, minivans, and crossovers and "Ram" for light- and medium-duty trucks and other commercial-use vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2011, Chrysler unveiled its "Imported From Detroit" campaign with ads featuring Detroit rapper Eminem, one of which aired during the Super Bowl.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The campaign highlighted the rejuvenation of the entire product lineup, which included the new, redesigned, and repackaged 2011 model year 200 sedans and 200 convertibles, the Chrysler 300 sedan, and the Chrysler Town & Country minivan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] As part of the campaign, Chrysler sold a line of clothing items featuring the Monument to Joe Louis, with proceeds being funneled to Detroit-area charities, including the Boys and Girls Clubs of Southeast Michigan, Habitat for Humanity Detroit and the Marshall Mathers Foundation.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In March 2011, Chrysler Group LLC filed a lawsuit against Moda Group LLC (owner of Pure Detroit clothing retailer) for copying and selling merchandise with the "Imported from Detroit" slogan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler claimed it had notified defendant of its pending trademark application February 14, but the defendant argued Chrysler had not secured a trademark for the "Imported From Detroit" phrase.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] District Judge Arthur Tarnow ruled that Chrysler's request did not show that it would suffer irreparable harm or that it had a strong likelihood of winning its case.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Therefore, Pure Detroit's owner, Detroit retailer Moda Group LLC, can continue selling its "Imported from Detroit" products.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Tarnow also noted that Chrysler does not have a trademark on "Imported from Detroit" and rejected the automaker's argument that trademark law is not applicable to the case.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In March 2012, Chrysler Group LLC and Pure Detroit agreed to a March 27 mediation to try to settle the lawsuit over the clothing company's use of "Imported from Detroit" slogan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Pure Detroit stated that Chrysler has made false claims about the origins of three vehicles - Chrysler 200, Chrysler 300 and Chrysler Town & Country - none of which are built in Detroit.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Pure Detroit also said that Chrysler's Imported From Detroit merchandise is not being made in Detroit.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2012 Chrysler and Pure Detroit came to an undisclosed settlement.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler's Jefferson North Assembly, which makes the Jeep Grand Cherokee and Dodge Durango, is the only car manufacturing plant of any company remaining entirely in Detroit (General Motors operates a plant that is partly in Detroit and partly in Hamtramck).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2011, Eminem settled a lawsuit against Audi alleging the defendant had ripped off the Chrysler 300 Super Bowl commercial in the Audi A6 Avant ad.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Again in 2012, Chrysler advertised during the Super Bowl.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Its two-minute February 5, 2012 Super Bowl XLVI advertisement was titled "Halftime in America".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The ad drew criticism from several leading U.S. conservatives, who suggested that its messaging implied that President Barack Obama deserved a second term and, as such, was political payback for Obama's support for the federal bailout of the company.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Asked about the criticism in a *60 Minutes* interview with Steve Kroft, Sergio Marchionne responded "just to rectify the record I paid back the loans at 19.7% Interest.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] I don't think I committed to do to a commercial on top of that" and characterized the Republican reaction as "unnecessary and out of place".
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] First introduced as MyGig, Chrysler Uconnect is a system that brings interactive ability to the in-car radio and telemetric-like controls to car settings.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] As of mid-2015, it was installed in hundreds of thousands of Fiat Chrysler vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] It connects to the Internet via the mobile network of AT&T, providing the car with its own IP address.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Internet connectivity using any Chrysler, Dodge, Jeep or Ram vehicle, via a Wi-Fi "hot-spot", is also available via Uconnect Web.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] According to Chrysler LLC, the hotspot range extends approximately 100 feet (30 m) from the vehicle in all directions, and combines both Wi-Fi and Sprint's 3G cellular connectivity.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Uconnect is available on several current and was available on several discontinued Chrysler models including the current Dodge Dart, Chrysler 300, Aspen, Sebring, Town and Country, Dodge Avenger, Caliber, Grand Caravan, Challenger, Charger, Journey, Nitro, and Ram.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In July 2015, IT security researchers announced a severe security flaw assumed to affect every Chrysler vehicle with Uconnect produced from late 2013 to early 2015.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] It allows hackers to gain access to the car over the Internet, and in the case of a Jeep Cherokee was demonstrated to enable an attacker to take control not just of the radio, A/C, and windshield wipers, but also of the car's steering, brakes and transmission.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler published a patch that car owners can download and install via a USB stick, or have a car dealer install for them.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Division that manufactured bearings and gears.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Division that built inboard, outboard engines, and various types of boats.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Desoto trucks were built and sold by Chrysler in Turkey until 1978, after which Askam took over the Turkish rights to the marque.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Name derived from the AMC Eagle model after Chrysler took over American Motors in 1987.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Replaced by Plymouth Trucks in the US in 1937 and folded into the Dodge Division after 1972 in Canada.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The Valiant was introduced in 1960 as a separate Chrysler brand, then was incorporated into the Plymouth line in the US starting in 1961.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1979, Chrysler, in cooperation with the United States Department of Energy, produced an experimental battery electric vehicle, the Chrysler ETV-1.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1992, Chrysler developed the Dodge EPIC concept minivan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 1993, Chrysler sold a limited-production electric minivan called the TEVan; only 56 were produced, mostly for electric utilities.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] A second generation, the EPIC (unrelated to the concept), was released in 1997 and discontinued in 1999.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler once owned the Global Electric Motorcars company, building low-speed neighborhood electric vehicles, but sold GEM to Polaris Industries in 2011.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In September 2007, Chrysler established ENVI, an in-house organization focused on electric-drive vehicles and related technologies which was disbanded by late 2009.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In August 2009, Chrysler took US$70 million in grants from the U.S.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Department of Energy to develop a test fleet of 220 hybrid pickup trucks and minivans.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The first hybrid models, the Chrysler Aspen hybrid and the Dodge Durango hybrid, were discontinued a few months after production in 2008, sharing its GM-designed hybrid technology with GM, Daimler and BMW.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Chrysler was on the Advisory Council of the PHEV Research Center, and undertook a government sponsored demonstration project with Ram and minivan vehicles.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] In 2012, FCA CEO Sergio Marchionne stated that Chrysler and Fiat planned to focus primarily on alternative fuels, such as compressed natural gas and diesel, instead of hybrid and electric drivetrains for its consumer products.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Fiat Chrysler bought a total of 8.2 million megagrams of U.S. greenhouse gas emission credits from competitors including Toyota, Honda, Tesla and Nissan for the 2010, 2011, 2013, and 2014 model years.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] It had the worst fleet average fuel economy among major manufacturers selling in the US from model years 2012–2023.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] The dedicated tank building division of Chrysler, this division was founded as the Chrysler Tank division in 1940, originally with the intention of providing another production line for the M2 Medium Tank, so that the U.S.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Army could more rapidly build up its inventory of the type.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] Its first plant was the Detroit Arsenal Tank Plant.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] After December 1941 and the United States' entry into the war against the Axis powers, the Tank division rapidly expanded, with new facilities such as the Tank Arsenal Proving Ground at (then) Utica, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p01] It also quickly widened the range of products it was developing and producing, including the M4 Sherman tank and the Chrysler A57 multibank tank engine.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] During World War II, essentially all of Chrysler's facilities were devoted to building military vehicles (the Jeep brand came later, after Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] They were also designing V12 and V16 hemi-engines producing 2,500 hp (1,864 kW; 2,535 PS) for airplanes, but they did not make it into production as jets were developed and were seen as the future for air travel.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] During the 1950s Cold War period, Chrysler made air raid sirens powered by its Hemi V-8 engines.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] When the Radiation Laboratory at MIT was established in 1941 to develop microwave radars, one of the first projects resulted in the SCR-584, the most widely recognized radar system of the war era.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] This system included a parabolic antenna six feet in diameter that was mechanically aimed in a helical pattern (round and round as well as up and down).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] One of Chrysler's most significant contributions to the war effort was in radar technology.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] For the final production design of this antenna and its highly complex drive mechanism, the Army's Signal Corps Laboratories turned to Chrysler's Central Engineering Office.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] There, the parabola was changed from aluminum to steel, allowing production to form using standard automotive presses.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] To keep weight down, 6,000 equally spaced holes were drilled in the face (this had no effect on the radiation pattern).
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] The drive mechanism was completely redesigned, using technology derived from Chrysler's research in automotive gears and differentials.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] The changes resulted in improved performance, reduced weight, and easier maintenance.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] A large portion of the Dodge plant was used in building 1,500 of the SCR-584 antennas as well as the vans used in the systems.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Army established the Ordnance Guided Missile Center (OGMC) at Redstone Arsenal, adjacent to Huntsville, Alabama.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] To form OGMC, over 1,000 civilian and military personnel were transferred from Fort Bliss, Texas.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Included was a group of German scientists and engineers led by Wernher von Braun; this group had been brought to America under Project Paperclip.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] OGMC designed the Army's first short-range ballistic missile, the PGM-11 Redstone, based on the WWII German V-2 missile.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Chrysler established the Missile Division to serve as the Redstone prime contractor, setting up an engineering operation in Huntsville and for production obtaining use from the U.S.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Navy of a large plant in Sterling Heights, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] The Redstone was in active service from 1958 until 1964; it was also the first missile to test-launch a live nuclear weapon, first detonated in a 1958 test in the South Pacific.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Working together, the Missile Division and von Braun's team greatly increased the capability of the Redstone, resulting in the PGM-19 Jupiter, a medium-range ballistic missile.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] In May 1959, a Jupiter missile launched two small monkeys into space in a nose cone; this was America's first successful flight and recovery of live space payloads.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Responsibility for deploying Jupiter missiles was transferred from the Army to the Air Force; armed with nuclear warheads, they were first deployed in Italy and Turkey during the early 1960s.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] In July 1959, NASA chose the Redstone missile as the basis for the Mercury-Redstone Launch Vehicle to be used for suborbital test flights of the Project Mercury spacecraft.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Three uncrewed MRLV launch attempts were made between November 1960 and March 1961, two of which were successful.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] The MRLV successfully launched the chimpanzee Ham, and astronauts Alan Shepard and Gus Grissom on three suborbital flights in January, May, and July 1961, respectively.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] America's more ambitious crewed space travel plans included the design of the Saturn series of heavy-lift launch vehicles by a team headed by Wernher von Braun.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Chrysler's Huntsville operation, then designated the Space Division, became Marshall Space Flight Center's prime contractor for the first stage of the Saturn I and Saturn IB versions.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] The design was based on a cluster of Redstone and Jupiter fuel tanks and Chrysler built it for the Apollo program in the Michoud Assembly Facility in East New Orleans, one of the largest manufacturing plants in the world.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] Between October 1961 and July 1975, NASA used ten Saturn Is and nine Saturn IBs for suborbital and orbital flights, all of which were successful; Chrysler missiles and boosters never suffered a launch failure.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-p02] The division was also a subcontractor which modified one of the mobile launcher platforms for use with the Saturn IB rockets using Saturn V infrastructure.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-royal-australia] The **Chrysler Royal** is an automobile which was produced by Chrysler Australia from 1957 to 1963.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-royal-australia] The doors and basic structure of the P25 sedan was retained, and with input from Australian and American Chrysler designers, the 1955 US Plymouth front sheetmetal was adapted to the P25 body and the rear quarter panels redesigned.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-royal-australia] They also added a wraparound rear windscreen, which caused development problems with Pilkington Glass, the Australian suppliers, who struggled to get the correct curved shape.
[src:chrysler-royal-australia/chrysler-royal-australia] The first version of the Chrysler Royal, the AP1, was introduced in May 1957.
